Molokhia!- w/ Mom’s Rice, Rima’s Relish, Green Zhug and Cilantro!
Limited Availability!

Molokhia is a braising green that is extremely healthy and delicious. It is considered one of the national dishes of Egypt and I grew up eating it my whole life. It is extremely rare to see this dish outside of an Arab home and is only found fresh at select farmer’s markets here in California.

Mushroom Paitan Ramen from last week 🍜🍄. I used the Vegan Ramen recipe from my blog as a base and added a Ajitama because I could not resist. I would usually add a roasted vegetables to this dish, but these noodles booked end a yakitori night so I held back.

I am getting hungry just thinking about it.

🎙It’s really happening!! Queens has found a home at 1235 9th Ave...and it’s going to be (dun, dun, dun)..a neighborhood Korean superette! It’s an ode to those charming east coast delis & Korean grocers we new and loved.
The Queens concept: think cozy, galley style deli-grocery filled with all the provisions one needs to whip up a delicious Korean meal at home, plus a rotating lineup of super tasty, traditional grab-and-go Korean dishes and fridge staples. Sounds like fun, right? 🥂
Opening summer 2019...stay tuned!
🌾메밀배추전 ~ napa cabbage - chive - buckwheat batter - pan fried in perilla oil.
[013] Tonkotsu Ramen 🍜🐷 - I hardly make Tonkotsu, but I have to admit this was really good. Added some gyofun which really completed the bowl. Time to turn this into tsukemen next.

Thinking about the #noodles I had at @afuripdx. I learned that Afuri decided to have it's first US location in Portland because their soft and pure water similar to what is going in Japan. Perfect for making noodles. I still have a lot of things to learn about noodle making! 🍜 #liftingnoodles
Happy May the 4th (be with you)! In honor of this day I will need to break out my #StarWars themed ramen bowls. How are you going to celebrate #maythe4thbewithyou ?

I’ve been traveling for the last few weeks so bear with me and my non-NC posts but I can’t help but share! We all know that I’m a snob when it comes to boba and Raleigh doesn’t have a lot of good spots, so I’ve been making it a point to hit all of them in CA. I’ve been dying to get my hands on @tigersugar.usa but since they aren’t on the west coast yet, I heard @yifang.cal was a close second. There’s a trend happening right now where boba shops cook their boba in brown sugar and honestly, I don’t know if I can go back to regular boba now. It’s so high in demand and takes hours to cook so if you’re not there when they come out, you’re not getting your hands on it. It’s usually served with fresh milk but I got mine with black milk tea! Swipe for the most satisfying mix ever 🤤

it’s not 🍑 day at the gym, but it’s 🍑 day in my house 💯 easiest ever sautéed peaches with coconut milk and a honey drizzle. next time i’ll add granola and ice cream on top, but for a beginner sautéed-peach-maker, this was pretty damn good!
slice one peach in half. add 1/2 tsp coconut oil to a cast iron skillet, medium heat. place peaches face down in the skillet for 2 minutes. flip to the other side for another two minutes. transfer to a plate, add some cinnamon, a drizzle of coconut milk and manuka honey, and heyyyyyyyy party in your mouth!

i’ll have you know that at this point, my freezer is one giant repository of all the leftover treats i make. most people store their frozen meals, fruit, veggies and the like, and i store baked goods, tahini chocolate chip cookies (the Life Changing kind), brownies, and these 🙊🤷🏻‍♀️ come hang out in my freezer and you can snack on some of these PEANUT BUTTER CHOCOLATE CHIP BITES! or you can make them! grab one package of @simplemills crunchy chocolate chip cookies, and top each one with @wild_friends creamy peanut butter, melted dairy free chocolate and sea salt! don’t forget the sea salt, it’s the best part. freeze for 30 minutes so everything hardens and that’s it 🤗 happy thursday, my friends!!!!! #kalejunkie

SWEET & SALTY CRUNCHY CHICKPEAS (like kettle corn but chickpeas) 💯 ok, so here’s what i want to say about these. if you’ve tried to make something similar in the past but they turned out soggy, then you need to follow my instructions below to get that CRUNCH factor! i like to snack on these by the handful, but you can also use them to top a salad or really anything that needs a little sumthin’ 🤷🏻‍♀️
.
first things first, grab two cans of garbanzo beans and put them in a strainer and rinse well. then lay them on a towel and pat dry and let air dry for an hour. so go run an errand or go to yoga or walk the dog. but the key is that they are DRY before you start, and if they aren’t then beware of the SOG 😐!
.
turn oven to 400. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. line up chickpeas in a single layer. roast for 30 minutes, stopping every 10 minutes to rotate them so that they dry out evenly, remove from oven, and transfer to a bowl.
.
for the SWEET & SALTY sauce, whisk together the following in a small bowl:
1 tb melted ghee (or avocado oil or olive oil)
2 tb honey (or maple syrup)
1 tsp sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon
.
coat the chickpeas evenly in the sauce and return to the baking sheet and back into the oven for 7-10 more minutes. they will be crispy and stay crispy! store extras in a glass container in the fridge

for all of your weekend baking needs, here is my gluten free/grain free BLACKBERRY COFFEE CAKE! and am i the only person that didn’t know that coffee cake doesn’t contain coffee? so why would anyone name a cake ‘coffee cake’ if it doesn’t contain coffee? 🙄🤷🏻‍♀️ it’s meant to be enjoyed WITH coffee, but it’s irrelevant anyway because this recipe is yummy and that’s really all you need to know🙊.
.
cake—
1 cup blackberries
1 cup almond flour
1/2 cup coconut flour
3 eggs
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/4 cup maple syrup
1 tsp baking soda
pinch sea salt
.
topping—
3/4 cup chopped walnuts
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
3 tb coconut sugar
.
preheat oven to 350. line an 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper (grease inside of pan first so the parchment paper sticks). make the topping first, by combining all ingredients in a medium bowl. mix well and set aside. now make the cake by adding all of the ingredients, except the blackberries, and blend until well incorporated. transfer to a medium bowl, and fold in the blackberries. mix well, and you can go ahead and crush some of the blackberries in the batter. pour half of the batter into the baking dish, followed by half of the topping. then add remaining batter and remaining topping. use a spatula to flatten and make even. bake for 40 minutes.
HAPPY SATURDAY AND ENJOY!!

i woke up thinking oh it’s toast tuesday, i should make toast, but instead i was craving a big ass smoothie and didn’t feel like taking pictures, so i’m sharing one of my all time favorite recipes with you, my PALEO CRUNCHY CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES! so good, guaranteed to bring all the boys to the yard 😂🙄🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️ kidding, sorta. here’s the recipe:
.
1 cup almond butter
3/4 cup coconut sugar
1 egg
1 tsp baking soda
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together all the ingredients except the chocolate chips. then fold in 1/2 of the chocolate chips. use a cookie scoop to form 10 cookies. make sure to spread them out because the dough spreads in the oven. sprinkle remaining chocolate chips on top. bake 12-13 minutes. remove from oven and let cool. they will flatten out some more and get a little more crunchy! #kalejunkie

did you know you can also BAKE Trader Joe’s cauliflower gnocchi and make a quick, one pan meal? they will still turn out nice and crunchy, and you can have dinner on your table in minutes! this is an ITALIAN INSPIRED ONE PAN CAULIFLOWER GNOCCHI and i’m super excited to tell you how i made it because you’ll be surprised how flavorful this meal is and how tasty healthy can be! again, ignore the preparation instructions on the gnocchi package and follow mine below!):
-
here’s what you need:
one package @traderjoes cauliflower gnocchi, frozen!
1/2 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
1-2 sweet bell peppers, roughly chopped
1 small red onion, thinly sliced
pinch chopped basil
2 tb avocado oil (or oil of choice)
2 tb italian seasoning
pinch of salt / pepper
parmesan cheese to top (optional)
-
here’s how to make it:
preheat oven to 425 degrees. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. combine all ingredients in a medium bowl and use your hands to ensure everything is coated well with the oil (if you use too much oil, the gnocchi will not be crunchy). pour contents from the bowl onto the baking sheet. bake for 20 minutes. remove from oven and use tongs to toss everything. bake for another 10 minutes. remove from oven and top with the parmesan cheese if you’d like! enjoy 😉 #kalejunkie

i’ll have you know that at this point, my freezer is one giant repository of all the leftover treats i make. most people store their frozen meals, fruit, veggies and the like, and i store baked goods, tahini chocolate chip cookies (the Life Changing kind), brownies, and these 🙊🤷🏻‍♀️ come hang out in my freezer and you can snack on some of these PEANUT BUTTER CHOCOLATE CHIP BITES! or you can make them! grab one package of @simplemills crunchy chocolate chip cookies, and top each one with @wild_friends creamy peanut butter, melted dairy free chocolate and sea salt! don’t forget the sea salt, it’s the best part. freeze for 30 minutes so everything hardens and that’s it 🤗 happy thursday, my friends!!!!! #kalejunkie

SWEET & SALTY CRUNCHY CHICKPEAS (like kettle corn but chickpeas) 💯 ok, so here’s what i want to say about these. if you’ve tried to make something similar in the past but they turned out soggy, then you need to follow my instructions below to get that CRUNCH factor! i like to snack on these by the handful, but you can also use them to top a salad or really anything that needs a little sumthin’ 🤷🏻‍♀️
.
first things first, grab two cans of garbanzo beans and put them in a strainer and rinse well. then lay them on a towel and pat dry and let air dry for an hour. so go run an errand or go to yoga or walk the dog. but the key is that they are DRY before you start, and if they aren’t then beware of the SOG 😐!
.
turn oven to 400. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. line up chickpeas in a single layer. roast for 30 minutes, stopping every 10 minutes to rotate them so that they dry out evenly, remove from oven, and transfer to a bowl.
.
for the SWEET & SALTY sauce, whisk together the following in a small bowl:
1 tb melted ghee (or avocado oil or olive oil)
2 tb honey (or maple syrup)
1 tsp sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon
.
coat the chickpeas evenly in the sauce and return to the baking sheet and back into the oven for 7-10 more minutes. they will be crispy and stay crispy! store extras in a glass container in the fridge

for all of your weekend baking needs, here is my gluten free/grain free BLACKBERRY COFFEE CAKE! and am i the only person that didn’t know that coffee cake doesn’t contain coffee? so why would anyone name a cake ‘coffee cake’ if it doesn’t contain coffee? 🙄🤷🏻‍♀️ it’s meant to be enjoyed WITH coffee, but it’s irrelevant anyway because this recipe is yummy and that’s really all you need to know🙊.
.
cake—
1 cup blackberries
1 cup almond flour
1/2 cup coconut flour
3 eggs
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/4 cup maple syrup
1 tsp baking soda
pinch sea salt
.
topping—
3/4 cup chopped walnuts
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
3 tb coconut sugar
.
preheat oven to 350. line an 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper (grease inside of pan first so the parchment paper sticks). make the topping first, by combining all ingredients in a medium bowl. mix well and set aside. now make the cake by adding all of the ingredients, except the blackberries, and blend until well incorporated. transfer to a medium bowl, and fold in the blackberries. mix well, and you can go ahead and crush some of the blackberries in the batter. pour half of the batter into the baking dish, followed by half of the topping. then add remaining batter and remaining topping. use a spatula to flatten and make even. bake for 40 minutes.
HAPPY SATURDAY AND ENJOY!!
#kalejunkie

i woke up thinking oh it’s toast tuesday, i should make toast, but instead i was craving a big ass smoothie and didn’t feel like taking pictures, so i’m sharing one of my all time favorite recipes with you, my PALEO CRUNCHY CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES! so good, guaranteed to bring all the boys to the yard 😂🙄🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️ kidding, sorta. here’s the recipe:
.
1 cup almond butter
3/4 cup coconut sugar
1 egg
1 tsp baking soda
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together all the ingredients except the chocolate chips. then fold in 1/2 of the chocolate chips. use a cookie scoop to form 10 cookies. make sure to spread them out because the dough spreads in the oven. sprinkle remaining chocolate chips on top. bake 12-13 minutes. remove from oven and let cool. they will flatten out some more and get a little more crunchy! #kalejunkie

did you know you can also BAKE Trader Joe’s cauliflower gnocchi and make a quick, one pan meal? they will still turn out nice and crunchy, and you can have dinner on your table in minutes! this is an ITALIAN INSPIRED ONE PAN CAULIFLOWER GNOCCHI and i’m super excited to tell you how i made it because you’ll be surprised how flavorful this meal is and how tasty healthy can be! again, ignore the preparation instructions on the gnocchi package and follow mine below!):
-
here’s what you need:
one package @traderjoes cauliflower gnocchi, frozen!
1/2 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
1-2 sweet bell peppers, roughly chopped
1 small red onion, thinly sliced
pinch chopped basil
2 tb avocado oil (or oil of choice)
2 tb italian seasoning
pinch of salt / pepper
parmesan cheese to top (optional)
-
here’s how to make it:
preheat oven to 425 degrees. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. combine all ingredients in a medium bowl and use your hands to ensure everything is coated well with the oil (if you use too much oil, the gnocchi will not be crunchy). pour contents from the bowl onto the baking sheet. bake for 20 minutes. remove from oven and use tongs to toss everything. bake for another 10 minutes. remove from oven and top with the parmesan cheese if you’d like! enjoy 😉 #kalejunkie

i woke up thinking oh it’s toast tuesday, i should make toast, but instead i was craving a big ass smoothie and didn’t feel like taking pictures, so i’m sharing one of my all time favorite recipes with you, my PALEO CRUNCHY CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES! so good, guaranteed to bring all the boys to the yard 😂🙄🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️ kidding, sorta. here’s the recipe:
.
1 cup almond butter
3/4 cup coconut sugar
1 egg
1 tsp baking soda
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together all the ingredients except the chocolate chips. then fold in 1/2 of the chocolate chips. use a cookie scoop to form 10 cookies. make sure to spread them out because the dough spreads in the oven. sprinkle remaining chocolate chips on top. bake 12-13 minutes. remove from oven and let cool. they will flatten out some more and get a little more crunchy! #kalejunkie

did you know you can also BAKE Trader Joe’s cauliflower gnocchi and make a quick, one pan meal? they will still turn out nice and crunchy, and you can have dinner on your table in minutes! this is an ITALIAN INSPIRED ONE PAN CAULIFLOWER GNOCCHI and i’m super excited to tell you how i made it because you’ll be surprised how flavorful this meal is and how tasty healthy can be! again, ignore the preparation instructions on the gnocchi package and follow mine below!):
-
here’s what you need:
one package @traderjoes cauliflower gnocchi, frozen!
1/2 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
1-2 sweet bell peppers, roughly chopped
1 small red onion, thinly sliced
pinch chopped basil
2 tb avocado oil (or oil of choice)
2 tb italian seasoning
pinch of salt / pepper
parmesan cheese to top (optional)
-
here’s how to make it:
preheat oven to 425 degrees. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. combine all ingredients in a medium bowl and use your hands to ensure everything is coated well with the oil (if you use too much oil, the gnocchi will not be crunchy). pour contents from the bowl onto the baking sheet. bake for 20 minutes. remove from oven and use tongs to toss everything. bake for another 10 minutes. remove from oven and top with the parmesan cheese if you’d like! enjoy 😉 #kalejunkie

They even have a discount for those who want to stick around and hang out.

I’ve been traveling for the last few weeks so bear with me and my non-NC posts but I can’t help but share! We all know that I’m a snob when it comes to boba and Raleigh doesn’t have a lot of good spots, so I’ve been making it a point to hit all of them in CA. I’ve been dying to get my hands on @tigersugar.usa but since they aren’t on the west coast yet, I heard @yifang.cal was a close second. There’s a trend happening right now where boba shops cook their boba in brown sugar and honestly, I don’t know if I can go back to regular boba now. It’s so high in demand and takes hours to cook so if you’re not there when they come out, you’re not getting your hands on it. It’s usually served with fresh milk but I got mine with black milk tea! Swipe for the most satisfying mix ever 🤤

i woke up thinking oh it’s toast tuesday, i should make toast, but instead i was craving a big ass smoothie and didn’t feel like taking pictures, so i’m sharing one of my all time favorite recipes with you, my PALEO CRUNCHY CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES! so good, guaranteed to bring all the boys to the yard 😂🙄🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️ kidding, sorta. here’s the recipe:
.
1 cup almond butter
3/4 cup coconut sugar
1 egg
1 tsp baking soda
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together all the ingredients except the chocolate chips. then fold in 1/2 of the chocolate chips. use a cookie scoop to form 10 cookies. make sure to spread them out because the dough spreads in the oven. sprinkle remaining chocolate chips on top. bake 12-13 minutes. remove from oven and let cool. they will flatten out some more and get a little more crunchy! #kalejunkie

SWEET & SALTY CRUNCHY CHICKPEAS (like kettle corn but chickpeas) 💯 ok, so here’s what i want to say about these. if you’ve tried to make something similar in the past but they turned out soggy, then you need to follow my instructions below to get that CRUNCH factor! i like to snack on these by the handful, but you can also use them to top a salad or really anything that needs a little sumthin’ 🤷🏻‍♀️
.
first things first, grab two cans of garbanzo beans and put them in a strainer and rinse well. then lay them on a towel and pat dry and let air dry for an hour. so go run an errand or go to yoga or walk the dog. but the key is that they are DRY before you start, and if they aren’t then beware of the SOG 😐!
.
turn oven to 400. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. line up chickpeas in a single layer. roast for 30 minutes, stopping every 10 minutes to rotate them so that they dry out evenly, remove from oven, and transfer to a bowl.
.
for the SWEET & SALTY sauce, whisk together the following in a small bowl:
1 tb melted ghee (or avocado oil or olive oil)
2 tb honey (or maple syrup)
1 tsp sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon
.
coat the chickpeas evenly in the sauce and return to the baking sheet and back into the oven for 7-10 more minutes. they will be crispy and stay crispy! store extras in a glass container in the fridge

did you know you can also BAKE Trader Joe’s cauliflower gnocchi and make a quick, one pan meal? they will still turn out nice and crunchy, and you can have dinner on your table in minutes! this is an ITALIAN INSPIRED ONE PAN CAULIFLOWER GNOCCHI and i’m super excited to tell you how i made it because you’ll be surprised how flavorful this meal is and how tasty healthy can be! again, ignore the preparation instructions on the gnocchi package and follow mine below!):
-
here’s what you need:
one package @traderjoes cauliflower gnocchi, frozen!
1/2 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
1-2 sweet bell peppers, roughly chopped
1 small red onion, thinly sliced
pinch chopped basil
2 tb avocado oil (or oil of choice)
2 tb italian seasoning
pinch of salt / pepper
parmesan cheese to top (optional)
-
here’s how to make it:
preheat oven to 425 degrees. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. combine all ingredients in a medium bowl and use your hands to ensure everything is coated well with the oil (if you use too much oil, the gnocchi will not be crunchy). pour contents from the bowl onto the baking sheet. bake for 20 minutes. remove from oven and use tongs to toss everything. bake for another 10 minutes. remove from oven and top with the parmesan cheese if you’d like! enjoy 😉 #kalejunkie

it’s not 🍑 day at the gym, but it’s 🍑 day in my house 💯 easiest ever sautéed peaches with coconut milk and a honey drizzle. next time i’ll add granola and ice cream on top, but for a beginner sautéed-peach-maker, this was pretty damn good!
slice one peach in half. add 1/2 tsp coconut oil to a cast iron skillet, medium heat. place peaches face down in the skillet for 2 minutes. flip to the other side for another two minutes. transfer to a plate, add some cinnamon, a drizzle of coconut milk and manuka honey, and heyyyyyyyy party in your mouth!
happy monday everyone!
#kalejunkie

for all of your weekend baking needs, here is my gluten free/grain free BLACKBERRY COFFEE CAKE! and am i the only person that didn’t know that coffee cake doesn’t contain coffee? so why would anyone name a cake ‘coffee cake’ if it doesn’t contain coffee? 🙄🤷🏻‍♀️ it’s meant to be enjoyed WITH coffee, but it’s irrelevant anyway because this recipe is yummy and that’s really all you need to know🙊.
.
cake—
1 cup blackberries
1 cup almond flour
1/2 cup coconut flour
3 eggs
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/4 cup maple syrup
1 tsp baking soda
pinch sea salt
.
topping—
3/4 cup chopped walnuts
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
3 tb coconut sugar
.
preheat oven to 350. line an 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper (grease inside of pan first so the parchment paper sticks). make the topping first, by combining all ingredients in a medium bowl. mix well and set aside. now make the cake by adding all of the ingredients, except the blackberries, and blend until well incorporated. transfer to a medium bowl, and fold in the blackberries. mix well, and you can go ahead and crush some of the blackberries in the batter. pour half of the batter into the baking dish, followed by half of the topping. then add remaining batter and remaining topping. use a spatula to flatten and make even. bake for 40 minutes.
HAPPY SATURDAY AND ENJOY!!

In my happy place. It was such an overwhelming pleasure to be able to experience the early, mid and late summer menus at @singlethreadfarms this season and get to see the development of dishes as peak seasonality of products changed. Every meal I’ve had at ST has been flawless perfection, which can pose a problem for a restaurant in how do they top the last experience?when I decided to do this, I was nervous maybe there wouldn’t be enough variation in the menus month to month for me to keep the upward trajectory of smitten-ness going full steam but I needn’t have worried. Somehow I always leave even more blown away than my previous trip to ST which is so beautiful. The synchronicity between all the teams is unreal. Service is warm, welcoming and comfortable while being simultaneously the most polished of any restaurant I’ve ever dined in. I really love how the customized reserve pairings have evolved as Alex and Alex have gained more knowledge of my personal tastes (though it was always fucking mind blowing). @kyleconnaughton’s food is always B-A-N-A-N-A-S amazing, and there is enough turnover in the menu to support multiple trips in a single season. I’ll post up all the food pics in a few days time and sorry to be repetitive but as I rambled on about the last time, the food is emotional, both incredibly exciting and new while also concurrently deeply nostalgic and familiar for a northern CA kid who grew up eating so many of these same produce varietals @lumberjackieo grows at the farm from my grandparent’s ranch not 20 miles away and saw so many of the same flowers grown at my grandma’s Petaluma plant nursery. I’m very grateful that @light_thief’s birthday, my birthday and now our wedding anniversary all fall a month-ish apart each so I have the perfect excuse to do this shit every year now as long as I can continue to finance this addiction. Thank you to all y’all on the ST team who always make us feel like family when we are there and continue to make every meal newly the best of my life each time, over and over. Also, deeply, deeply appreciate you guys sharing some of that really special bottle with us. 🙏🏻

Was excited to try the char kway teow from this place as I haven’t had Malaysian food in a long time. Was surprised to see these thin rice noodles (rehydrated from dried rice noodles). The flavors were nice, even though there was no heat (char kway teow is supposed to be spicy) but the use of rehydrated noodles is disappointing for a restaurant based in the Bay Area. It’s not the middle of Milan (where I ate Chinese food last week). Freshly made flat rice noodles are readily available. char kway teow uses the flat rice noodles like in beef hor fun, not these skinny pad Thai noodles. For $15.99(?) they can afford to use fresh noodles of the right kind. 📍: 10895 S Blaney Ave Cupertino CA

This is ME:Dessert Story. ❤️ DEETS⠀
📍U:Dessert Story • San Francisco, CA • @udessertstory 🍵 SF Foodie Scene darling. Beautifully crafted, unique Korean, Japanese & Thai inspired sweets. The bingsoo is their supsertar (I didn't want something cold)- they even have one on fire! ⠀
🍵 Interior is like a Euro-inspired-Korean-inspired little cafe. (There's lotsa whimsical cafes in Korea that mix pastel-y storybook & European aesthetics.) ⠀
🍵 Cozy: Fills up fast (tables often shared). For insta foodies: Hard to take photos at extended distances. But! Romantic sitting close with the one you love over desserts
🍵 PICTURED (clockwise from top): Thai Crepe Cake, Blue Lychee, Matcha Lava Cake, Salted Caramel Cheese Foam Drink.⠀
🍵 FAVE of the 4: Matcha Lava Cake: Like a cakey, soft dark chocolate truffle with thick, darkly sweet ritual grade matcha "lava". I love matcha & dark chocolate. Powder dusting added to the truffle feel.⠀
🍵 I enjoyed the foam drink (nice, thick foam- tasted great with salted caramel) & the very lychee-infused Blue Lychee (whole Lychee inside!).⠀

You should’ve seen the look on my face when i took my first sip of the Black Sesame Latte.
i can’t even begin to describe how amazing this place was, so just fly to SF and see for yourself. ☕️ Black Sesame Latte ($6.75) was outrageously expensive but was out. of. this. world.
nutty, creamy, totally black sesame-y, and just the right bit of sweetness (i got my half sweet btw)
🍪 Matcha White Chocolate Cookie ($3) also hella pricey for a smol litto cookie that i could’ve easily finished in a bite but Stonemill knows how to make a good cookie - dense, moist, and soft 🍫 Black Sesame Chocolate Tart ($7) was crazy delicious. chocolate tart shell, matcha & black sesame layers under a rich ganache, topped with chocolate pearls and matcha sable
This place has stolen my heart and also the title for my favorite place in SF so far (sorry, Mr. Holmes) 🖤🍵💚

SWEET & SALTY CRUNCHY CHICKPEAS (like kettle corn but chickpeas) 💯 ok, so here’s what i want to say about these. if you’ve tried to make something similar in the past but they turned out soggy, then you need to follow my instructions below to get that CRUNCH factor! i like to snack on these by the handful, but you can also use them to top a salad or really anything that needs a little sumthin’ 🤷🏻‍♀️
.
first things first, grab two cans of garbanzo beans and put them in a strainer and rinse well. then lay them on a towel and pat dry and let air dry for an hour. so go run an errand or go to yoga or walk the dog. but the key is that they are DRY before you start, and if they aren’t then beware of the SOG 😐!
.
turn oven to 400. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. line up chickpeas in a single layer. roast for 30 minutes, stopping every 10 minutes to rotate them so that they dry out evenly, remove from oven, and transfer to a bowl.
.
for the SWEET & SALTY sauce, whisk together the following in a small bowl:
1 tb melted ghee (or avocado oil or olive oil)
2 tb honey (or maple syrup)
1 tsp sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon
.
coat the chickpeas evenly in the sauce and return to the baking sheet and back into the oven for 7-10 more minutes. they will be crispy and stay crispy! store extras in a glass container in the fridge

it’s not 🍑 day at the gym, but it’s 🍑 day in my house 💯 easiest ever sautéed peaches with coconut milk and a honey drizzle. next time i’ll add granola and ice cream on top, but for a beginner sautéed-peach-maker, this was pretty damn good!
slice one peach in half. add 1/2 tsp coconut oil to a cast iron skillet, medium heat. place peaches face down in the skillet for 2 minutes. flip to the other side for another two minutes. transfer to a plate, add some cinnamon, a drizzle of coconut milk and manuka honey, and heyyyyyyyy party in your mouth!

welcome to muffin monday 🤷🏻‍♀️ or should i say CHOCOLATE CHUNK TAHINI MUFFINS and it’s probably a good idea that you call in sick from work today to stay home and make them, i’m just saying 😎 i’ve been getting a lot of requests for banana-free recipes, so here’s one for you guys. these muffs are also paleo friendly, dairy free, gluten free, grain free, and taste like they came straight from a bakery! the recipe makes 5 large muffins or 8 regular size muffins. here’s how to make them👇🏼
.
1/3 cup coconut flour
1/3 cup almond flour
1/4 cup coconut sugar
1/2 tsp baking soda
1/2 tsp baking powder
pinch sea salt
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1/4 cup @obourfoods tahini
2 eggs
1 tsp vanilla
3/4 cup @hukitchen chocolate gems
.
preheat oven to 375. line muffin tin with liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together all of the dry ingredients and set aside. in another bowl, whisk together the coconut oil, tahini, eggs, and vanilla. pour bowl with dry ingredients into the wet ingredients. fold in the chocolate pieces. use a spoon to fill the muffin cavities, making 5 large muffins or 8 regular size. bake for 20 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean. enjoy!!!!!!!!!! #kalejunkie

Scrambled egg time is my favorite time 😋 as you may have noticed I don’t tend to add much seasoning to mine: a pinch of quality salt is all that’s needed for these beauties 😋 my friends over @spicetribe recently launched their single origin spices (you may remember me using their mixed spice blends for my salmon and lamb recipes), and their Peruvian pink salt is perfect for adding to these eggs! More dEATS on my IG stories. For a limited time, to celebrate @spicetribe’s single origin spice launch, they’re giving 35% off to all online orders of $20 or more, with code SPICE35! 🎉🎉🎉 other than the Peruvian pink salt, they also have late harvest black pepper corn, turmeric, smoked paprika, cumin seeds, coriander seeds, saffron and more! @spicetribe sources these from small farms around the world that are known for producing these unique spices, therefore supporting the livelihood of these farmers too 💓 Served these scrambled eggs with some toasts, applewood smoked bacon from Trader Joe’s and avocado 👌🏻👌🏻
.

My favorite spring roll 🦐place and my second favorite Pho spot 🍜 are both located at the Lion Plaza in San Jose!😍
-
1️⃣Thien Huong: Nem nuong rolls (grilled pork spring rolls) from Thien Huong are my favorite spot to get them in the Bay Area!!
.
2️⃣Pho Pasteur: The Pho is from Pho Pasteur which is very underrated in my opinion! Ask for thick noodles if you go! (Swipe to see 👉)
.
3️⃣CD Bakery:The shrimp spring rolls are from CD bakery which are some really solid spring rolls! Highly recommended if you want a cheap lunch!
-
The Lion Plaza food court has so many hidden gems that don't even show up on yelp! You can definitely get some of the most authentic Viet food over there! 🔥 🔥🔥
-
😍Tag your Viet food buddy!
-
📍Lion Plaza Food Court (SJ)
—

Mushroom Paitan Ramen from last week 🍜🍄. I used the Vegan Ramen recipe from my blog as a base and added a Ajitama because I could not resist. I would usually add a roasted vegetables to this dish, but these noodles booked end a yakitori night so I held back.

I am getting hungry just thinking about it.

Congratulations to @ramen.chef and @taishoken.usa for opening up an amazing ramen shop! 🎊 I remember it was not too long ago where Yoshi talked about opening up his own shop. All the hard work that he put in really shows in the quality of the shop. This easily makes my Top 3 list of ramen in the US. For a moment, I felt like I was eating ramen back in Japan. 🍜

I was very fortunate to get a sneak peak of his ramen this past Friday and try out 3 of their ramen. Their Tokusei Tsukemen, Ramen, and Spicy Ramen.

The meal started with their potato salad with an ajitama and salted mullet roe. Something so simple was so delicious. It was preview of the rest of the meal to come.

The Tokusei Ramen brings a rich broth of pork and chicken that coats your mouth. The flavors were very balanced with from the first to the last sip. It came with medium-thin noodles that had a very smooth slurp and a pleasant chew.
My biggest complaint with spicy ramen is that the spice is very one dimensional. The Spicy Tokusei Ramen was very complex - smokey, floral, with a little bit of heat. I scratch my head trying to pick out all of the flavors. Just like the regular ramen this bowl was balanced.

My favorite bowl of the night is the Tokusei Tsukemen. The gyokai dipping broth was a nice balance of pork, chicken, and fish flavors. The real star of this dish were the noodles. Thick, chewy, and buckwheat forward flavors. The noodles are made in house and it really shows.

The best bowls of ramen to me are ones that are always balanced. At Taishoken, I had 3 bowls that were completely different and they were each made with the same amount of thoughtfulness, with every component meaningful to the bowl.

The grand opening is this Wednesday, July 17th, so get your bowl before the word spreads and the 1-2 hour waits begin!

My homemade ramen noodles after a week of resting. They have developed a slurpier and smoother texture.

Even though these noodles are at 36% hydration, they have a slight hard bite to them similar to hakata style noodles. It might be that whole wheat flour needs more water that just bread flour by itself.

I am ready to move on to my next batch so I can learn more. 👨🏻‍🔬 Definitely going to make less than 10 servings though. I don't eat as many noodles as I used to.

sunday calls for my PROCIUTTO, ARUGULA & LEMON PIZZA, made with a cauliflower pizza crust! it’s super easy to make, super flavorful, and yes—you can eat the lemon! if you want to try it in person, meet me tomorrow at the @specialtyfoodassociation’s winter fancy food show—i’ll be at the @caulipowered booth (#6719) from 11:30am-12pm, and they will be making them on-site. otherwise, go grab one of these pizza crusts and try the recipe!
.
1 @caulipowered plain crust pizza
1/2 cup pizza sauce
1/4 cup shredded sheep milk pecorino cheese
2 oz prosciutto
1 meyer lemon, thinly sliced
small handful arugula
everything but the bagel seasoning
.
preheat oven to 425 and place pizza crust on a baking sheet. spread a thin layer of pizza sauce evenly, followed by the cheese and the lemon slices. bake for 13 minutes. remove from oven, top with prosciutto, arugula and everything but the bagel seasoning. slice and enjoy! #caulipowered #ad

when you have nothing left in the fridge except Hu chocolate, a stale loaf of bread, lemons, and a lonely sweet potato, you make SWEET POTATO FRIES 🍟! i paired them with an easy LEMON TAHINI DIPPING SAUCE, and it’s pretty much my favorite snack/meal evaaaaa! here’s how to make PERFECT SWEET POTATO FRIES!
-
1 large sweet potato (with the orange flesh!)
2 tb avocado oil
1/2 tsp sea salt
seasonings of choice (sprinkle on anything you like, i don’t obsess over measurements, just sprinkle and have fun—garlic powder, oregano, cumin, etc. i used @primalpalate seafood seasoning bc it’s lemony and yum!)
-
dipping sauce—
1/4 cup tahini
juice of one lemon
2 garlic cloves, mashed
1/2 tsp sea salt
1/4 tsp cumin
4-6 TB water (to thin)
-
here’s how to make it:
preheat oven to 425. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. wash and scrub sweet potato. cut it in half and then cut into fries, about 1/2 inch thick. place sweet potato fries into a bowl and cover with the avocado oil and seasonings. use your hands to coat well. spread in a single layer onto the baking sheet. bake for 28-30 minutes, flipping once at the halfway point. for the dipping sauce, add tahini, lemon, mashed garlic, salt and cumin to a small bowl and whisk together. it will be thick! add water sparingly until desired consistency is reached! taste, adjust seasonings as needed, and enjoy! #kalejunkie

i never really considered myself a MORNING GLORY MUFFIN kind of gal, but wouldn’t you know, here i am 👵🏼 i made a version of my girl @lauraleabalanced’s jumbo morning glory muffins, and yeah...pretty convinced that you’re going to be obsessed too 💯 you can find the original (banana-less) recipe on laura’s blog, and my version is here for you below! you can see what they look like inside on my IG stories. -
ingredients:
1 cup rolled oats
1 cup gluten free flour (or whole wheat or spelt)
1 banana
2 eggs
2 tsp baking soda
1 apple (i like pink lady)
2 medium carrots
1/2 cup raisins
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 tsp nutmeg
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup coconut sugar
2 tsp vanilla extract
1/2 cup walnuts, chopped
pinch sea salt
-
instructions:
preheat oven to 350 and line a muffin tin with liners. in a medium bowl, mix together 1/2 cup of the oats, baking soda, flour, sea salt, coconut sugar, cinnamon, and nutmeg. set aside. in a food processor or blender, add remaining oats and pulse/blend until a flour consistency is formed, set aside. in another bowl, whisk together the eggs, vanilla, and coconut milk. next, core the apple, peel carrots, and add them to the blender, along with the banana. pulse/blend lightly until a crumble like consistency is formed. pour wet ingredients into dry, and fold in the raisins and walnuts, be sure not to overmix! spoon batter into each muffin cavity. i made regular size muffins and 28 min in the oven was perfect!

show of hands 🖐🏼 🖐🏼 🖐🏼 who wants the recipe for my new PALEO LEMON POPPYSEED MUFFINS? the answer should be yes and yes 😉 they are soft and moist (sorry, i went there) and coming this week on my feed and on kalejunkie.com. i just want to test it one more time to make sure it’s absolutely perfect for you 😍 hope your week is off to a great start! #kalejunkie

tested. retested. and tested again, here is the recipe for my new PALEO LEMON POPPYSEED MUFFINS 🍋 eeeeeeeeek they are so good, and i think some of my taste tester friends would agree (tell us, what did you think @biohackertodd? 😉) note, i haven’t tested all the substitutions, so if your diet allows, i’d suggest just making them as is! 🍋
-
here’s what you need for the muffins:
2 1/4 cups almond flour
1/2 cup arrowroot flour
3 eggs
1/2 cup lemon juice (this is 4-5 lemons)
zest of two lemons
1/2 cup maple syrup
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1 1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp baking soda
3 tb poppyseeds
1/4 tsp cinnamon
1/2 tsp salt
-
here’s how to make them:
preheat oven to 350. line a muffin tin with 12 liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together the eggs, lemon juice, lemon zest, maple syrup, coconut oil, and vanilla extract. you can also use a hand mixer to do this, but it’s not necessary. in another medium bowl, mix together the almond flour, arrowroot flour, baking soda, poppyseeds, cinnamon, and salt. pour dry batter into the wet, mixing together, but being careful not to overmix. use a spoon to fill each muffin tin cup almost to the top. bake for 17-18 minutes—the top will start to brown and a toothpick will come out clean.
-
for the drizzle, you’ve got options:
if you like your muffins a little sweeter, whisk together 1 cup of powdered sugar and 3 tb water, until desired consistency is reached, and drizzle over each muffin.
you could also whisk together 1/2 coconut butter with 1/4 cup maple syrup, thinning with a little water as needed.
-
ENJOYYYYYY!!!!! #kalejunkie

Homemade BLT, but instead of bacon, the B in this sandwich is for brisket. This brisket, lettuce, and tomato sandwich contains leftovers from the slow cooker brisket tacos I shared last week, little gem lettuce, heirloom tomato, and a little kewpie mayo stuffed in a bolillo. Served it with homemade pickled chilies and zucchini, plus @hawaiianbrandsnacks chips (courtesy of Spouse’s free work snacks). Bacon is great and all but I found my redefined BLT to be heartier for a dinner sandwich. Plus, it was a successful transformation of leftovers, which I’m always trying to encourage others (and myself!) to approach as a fun challenge in the kitchen.

What would you choose for your BLT— bacon or brisket?

Happy Friday! 🙌🏻🙌🏻I am excited to share another lamb recipe using #grassfed New Zealand lamb from @atkinsranch @beefandlambnz that I picked up from my local @wholefoods. I cut the lamb leg steak into small pieces, quickly tossed them with some cumin powder, chili powder and salt, and made them into skewers with some organic green bell peppers and red onion. Then I cooked them on the grill, along with some apricots - for a Mediterranean-inspired recipe. To serve, simply pair the kebabs with whole milk Greek yogurt on a plate, drizzle with extra virgin olive oil and place the grilled apricots on top of the Greek yogurt. So delicious! 🙀🙀😻😻I like to make extra kebabs to bring for lunch later in the week too. What I also love about Atkins Ranch is that it is the first lamb producer in the world to achieve Non-GMO Project verification, and the first lamb producer globally to achieve Global Animal Partnership’s Step 4 animal welfare certification💓. You can find out more about grass-fed beef and lamb from NZ and Atkins Ranch here: https://beefandlambnz.com https://atkinsranch.com Get yours from your local @wholefoods! 🙌🏻 @certifiedgap, @nongmoproject, @nourishwithlamb #tastepurenature #makesmewhole #partner #foodietribe @foodietribe #pastureraised #healthyeating #eatpretty #beautifulcuisines #和食 #和食ごはん

Decisions, decisions. Would you check out the size of that wine list!? 🍷 Raise your hand if you’ve ever been intimidated by a wine list at a nice restaurant? 🙋🏼‍♀️ I think we’ve all been there and that’s ok. There’s a lot of information in there, and unless you’ve studied the wines of the world or are a sommelier, a lot of it just looks like words on a page. When in these situations it’s easy to fall back on what you know and order something safe, but what’s the fun in that!? Next time, take a long look at the list, don’t get intimidated but instead be curious. 📖 Biggest advice I can give you - ask the sommelier for help. That’s why they are there and they want to help you! They will not judge you or your wine preferences, I promise. Either tell them, you’d like something that would pair well with your entrees or tell them what you typically like to drink; varietal, producer, region, etc and they may find you a new favorite wine! Wine is all about exploration. When I see a large wine list I used to get nervous, now I’m like a kid in a candy shop. 🤗 Which one are you? .

Mushroom #Vegan ramen is the noodle dish you didn't know you wanted. Lucky for you it is quick to make and a great substitute for tonkotsu ramen lovers. Check out the recipe link in my bio. This is the same recipe that I served at my Portland Popup with @kukiesslurpshack!

This weekend was one of the rare times that I make ramen for my parents. I do see my parents once a week, but I have been very fortunate and spoiled to have a home cook meal prepared for me when I visit.

When I do cook for my parents, I want to make it special, yet simple and healthy. I started with a very simple chicken stock made from @maryschicken. The stock was so clean and refreshing it was worth spending a few extra bucks. The golden broth was combined with a Mushroom Shoyu Tare leftover from my last popup. I topped the bowl with some asparagus sauteed in garlic, some kurobuta tenderloin, and of course a marinade egg.

My parents are people of few words when it comes to describing tasty food, but will speak volumes when they eat something they don't like. I didn't hear any complaints and my mom saved her leftover broth for later, so I will take that as a win.

Cooking at my parents house always reminds me of the beginning of my ramen journey. It is always good to reflect on the past every once and a while and evaluate my progress before looking towards the future and seeing what is next.

Tantanmen testing for my next pop-up on May 11th 👨🏻‍🔬🌶️. Stay tuned for more details.

I started with the mushroom/cashew base that I used for my latest Vegan Ramen and amped it up with some sesame paste, peanut butter, garlic, and soy sauce. It is always amazing to see how a few ingredients can transform it into something completely different. It is topped with a little bit of szechuan peppercorns and ichimi to give it a little kick. My chili oil is a work in progress, but the habanero peppers I added pushed it in the right direction.

i woke up thinking oh it’s toast tuesday, i should make toast, but instead i was craving a big ass smoothie and didn’t feel like taking pictures, so i’m sharing one of my all time favorite recipes with you, my PALEO CRUNCHY CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES! so good, guaranteed to bring all the boys to the yard 😂🙄🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️🤸🏻‍♀️ kidding, sorta. here’s the recipe:
.
1 cup almond butter
3/4 cup coconut sugar
1 egg
1 tsp baking soda
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together all the ingredients except the chocolate chips. then fold in 1/2 of the chocolate chips. use a cookie scoop to form 10 cookies. make sure to spread them out because the dough spreads in the oven. sprinkle remaining chocolate chips on top. bake 12-13 minutes. remove from oven and let cool. they will flatten out some more and get a little more crunchy! #kalejunkie

my smoothies are super basic, so i never really post them here 🤷🏻‍♀️ but here it is in case you want to try something different—THE smoothie i have almost every day, in one form or another! for protein powder, these days i just do one scoop of collagen peptides bc it gives me the most bang for my buck...protein + the hair, skin, nails and joint benefits. if you are looking for a plant based protein, i highly recommend @lilsipper’s protein collaboration with @nuzest_usa. it tastes great, it’s super clean, and great for people with gut sensitivities! anyway, here’s my recipe:
.
1 frozen banana
1 1/2 cups non dairy milk (coconut, almond, oat, or flax milk)
1 tb cacao powder
1 tb almond butter (pecan, hazelnut and peanut are super yummy too!)
1 tsp maca powder (don’t skip this superfood, it has tons of health benefits, including hormone balance, increased energy, mood booster, etc)
1 scoop collagen peptides (or protein powder of choice)
.
blend all the ingredients in a high speed blender and add any toppings of choice. note—if i make this smoothie post workout, i’ll add one scoop @mrm_usa BCAA +glutamine to reduce muscle soreness and for muscle repair.
oh, and my latest addition is adding 1/2 cup cold brew coffee for a little pick-me-up ☕️ have a great week everyone!

Happy almost Friday! As promised, I’m sharing this California roll recipe - I served them with a bed of mixed greens + seared ahi tuna for the perfect veggie + protein + carb experience 🙂 you can look through my IG highlights for how I make standard maki rolls, and for cali rolls, use the following filling: crab salad (dEATS below), avocado (cut into 1cm strips) and cucumber (cut into 1 cm strips). For the crab salad: use imitation crab shredded (you can pull them apart by hand depending on the brand, some easier than others, or chop roughly with a knife) and mixed with enough Japanese or avocado mayonnaise (choose a creamy and low acidity mayonnaise) such as @hellmannsmayonnaise until desired taste is achieved. It’s so simple but I absolutely love imitation crab + mayo. I mean, I love real crab as well. But imitation crab has this super addictive flavor that I cannot resist. I always get it in poke too 😅😅🤣🤣 don’t judge me! .

Fishbone crouton. This is an extension to our caesar salad dish featuring Bay Area sardines; meant to be eaten as a snack. The sardine bones are salted, rinsed and dried, smoked, and then lightly fried. Before serving they are seasoned with a mixture of bread ingredients. This mixture includes grains that are fermented, sprouted, grilled, and dried. We ground the mixture to a powder and add yeast. The result is a crunchy crouton with flavors of smoky dried bread. Tasty use of the entire fish. 📸 @croissantsandcaviar and @engagingaesthetics

BACK TO BASICS 🍌 when you want a banana bread that contains no added sugar (sweetened only from banana), but still tastes like it came from a bakery, you make this anything but basic CINNAMON BANANA BREAD 🙌🏼 it’s different than your usual banana bread in that it’s lighter — it’s not a dense brick that will sit in your stomach all day, but rather a soft and chewy pillow with a slightly crunchy top 😉 did i convince you yet? i’ve included the recipe for you below, and i’ll get it up on the blog later today so you can find it anytime! happy tuesday! ❤️ #kalejunkie
-
1 1/2 cups almond flour
1/4 cup tapioca flour
3 tb coconut flour
4 super ripe bananas (if they are large, use 3)
3 eggs
1 tsp vanilla extract
2 tb cinnamon
1 tsp baking soda
1 tsp baking powder
1/2 tsp sea salt
note: ** you can add any toppings you want, chocolate chips, nuts, etc.
-
preheat oven to 350. line a loaf pan with parchment paper (spray inside with oil first so paper sticks). in a medium bowl, whisk together dry ingredients. in a blender, blend the bananas and wet ingredients for about 10-15 seconds until just incorporated (some chunks are ok!). pour wet ingredients into the bowl with the dry ingredients and mix lightly until combined. pour into the loaf pan and smooth out the top with a spatula. bake for 40-45 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean. let cool, sprinkle a little more cinnamon on top and enjoyyyyyyy 🙌🏼🙌🏼🙌🏼🙌🏼🙌🏼🙌🏼

happy saturday everyone! ☀️ i’m off to get a much needed workout in, MEDITATE (i know, who dis 🤷🏻‍♀️💆🏻‍♀️) and then spend the day with the boys! they are both now in preschool full days so i look forward to the weekends to connect with them—time flies you guys, and nope, there are no more minis in my future 😂
.
i’ve got some new PALEO FUDGY BROWNIES for you guys. they are super fudgy and chewy, filled with chocolate chips, and yet still light! so if you are looking for something to bake today, i’ve got you!
.
here’s how to make them:
3 eggs
1/2 cup coconut sugar
1/2 cup almond flour
2 tb coconut flour
3 tb cacao powder
1/4 cup coffee, cooled
3/4 cup dairy free chocolate chips
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
pinch sea salt
.
preheat oven to 325. line an 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper and set aside (oil the baking dish so paper sticks). in a medium bowl, whisk together the eggs and coconut sugar for about two minutes, until well combined and there are no clumps. stir in the almond flour, coconut flour, cacao, coffee, coconut oil, and sea salt. mix until combined. fold in the chocolate chips. pour batter into the baking dish. bake for 35-37 minutes, or until a toothpick comes out clean! remove from oven and slice into 12 squares. enjoyyyyyyyy! #kalejunkie

happy saturday everyone! i’m finally rolling out my PALEO COPYCAT SAMOA RECIPE in case you want to do something fun in the kitchen this weekend! i forgot i teased it here on my page a few weeks ago and then didn’t share the recipe—i feel like i’m in a thousand places lately and forgetting things 🙊🙈! note, you need cookie cutters :) if you make these, be sure to tag me so i can share 😉 off to spend the day with my boys!
.
for the cookie base:
3/4 cup coconut flour
3 tb arrowroot or tapioca flour
1 tsp vanilla
1/4 cup maple syrup
pinch salt
1/2 cup coconut oil, melted
.
for the cookie layer:
3/4 cup unsweetened shredded coconut + extra to sprinkle on top
1/2 cup coconut milk
3 tb honey
3 tb almond butter
*chocolate of choice to dip!
.
preheat oven to 325. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together the ingredients for the cookie base, forming a ball. slightly roll and flatten onto the parchment paper. you need a 3 inch and a 1 inch cookie cutter. form 8 cookies using the cookie cutters. line them up on the baking sheet. bake 10-11 minutes until the cookies are just set and remove from oven. next, make the cookie layer. in a food processor, add coconut, coconut milk, honey and almond butter. the dough should be super thick and sticky. assemble the cookies — add about 2 tb of the cookie mixture on top of each cookie (I found it easiest to roll dough into small worms 🐛 and press onto each cookie). melt chocolate in the microwave in 30 second increments. drizzle chocolate on top of each cookie. add more shredded coconut if you’d like. place in fridge for 1-2 hours until set! #kalejunkie

morning 👋🏼 today i’m sharing ZUCCHINI CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES, of the vegan kind. i had a few super ripe bananas around yesterday and one lonely zucchini, so i made these cookies and added @hukitchen df paleo chocolate GEMS because they are crack! here’s how i made them:
.
2 large spotty bananas
3/4 cup shredded zucchini
1 cup gluten free rolled oats
3/4 cup almond flour
1/2 cup walnuts (optional)
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted and cooled
1/4 cup maple syrup
1 tsp cinnamon
1 tsp salt
1 tsp baking soda
3/4 cup dairy free chocolate (code KALEJUNKIE saves you 10% off all @hukitchen orders!)
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. shred your zucchini—you must take paper towels and soak up as much moisture as you can! in a medium bowl, mash the bananas well. then add shredded zucchini, and the other wet ingredients. in another bowl, mix together the dry ingredients and then pour into the bowl with the wet. fold in the chocolate chips. use a cookie scoop and form 12 cookies. bake for 12-14 minutes. they should still look a little soft when removed from the oven, that’s okay! they settle nicely. store in the fridge for up to one week! #kalejunkie

caption_text: First bowl of Ramen on my NYC trip. Met up with @the_original_kano and @ramenover for some fancy smancy tonkotsu at @tonchinnewyork . Do you know what? This bowl was awesome. I have gotten tired of tonkotsu lately and this bowl has made me a fan once again. It wasn't too heavy and more complex then just porky gelatanous soup. The egg and chashu were amazing and they make their own noodles too. Just the right amount of bite. I love how they designed everything to match, from the napkins and bowls down the the walls. It was an $18 bowl of ramen but it was delicious none the less. 🐷🍜

Homemade Taiwanese Beef Noodle Soup by my wife using @thewoksoflife recipe. 🐄🍜 It has been too hot the past few weeks to make ramen. So the day we made beef noodle soup, our place got up to 90 degrees inside so we finally budged and turned on the AC. Fall cannot come soon enough, but for now I will have to sweat it out while my broth turns my place into a sauna.
Of course I had to use ramen noodles in my bowl. The temomi noodles from @sunnoodles was pretty good, but the noodles for beef noodle soup needs to have a higher hydration for a chewier bite. We used udon for our second time which paired very well.

Shoyu Ramen testing 🍜🧪 I cracked open a few bottles of soy sauce that I had in my pantry for a while. The one that got my attention is a double brewed (saishikomi) soy sauce. This is where the produces uses already brewed soy sauce in the place of water and salt in the normal brewing process. It is not overly salty, but has an intense umami flavor that almost tasted fishy to me.

I am hoping to make a simple recipe that anyone can make at home. This recipe is so far so good! I want to tweak it a bit before posting. The made the bowl with some homemade noodles and I am pretty satisfied with how it turned out!

Who else likes shoyu ramen? I haven't really been a big fan, but I am getting more and more into it!
Yes, we have Topo Chico! For all you sparkling water heads. (And fried chicken for the rest of us)

this is a slice of my no-sugar-added cinnamon banana bread (recipe two posts back!) topped with @georgiagrinders hazelnut butter and homemade raspberry chia jam.
-
to make your own raspberry chia jam, it’s SO EASY! you can also sub raspberries with strawberries, blueberries, blackberries, etc.
-
1️⃣ place a small sauce pan on the stove.
2️⃣ add 1 cup raspberries, 1 teaspoon coconut oil, 1 tablespoon maple syrup (optional), and 2 tablespoons chia seeds.
3️⃣ turn on heat to low, and mix everything together, mashing the raspberries to your liking.
4️⃣ continue stirring for approximately 5 minutes, then remove from heat and let sit for 5 more minutes to thicken.
#kalejunkie

when that shadow hits justtttt right 😎😎😎 i made these GARLIC & ROSEMARY SWEET POTATO FRIES to go with my dinner last night and i wanted to share with you guys because they came out SO GOOD!
-
all you have to do is turn your oven to 400. chop two medium size japanese sweet potatoes into 1/2 inch thick pieces (like fries). toss them in a bowl, and coat with 3 tb avocado oil, 2 tb arrowroot flour, 1/2 tsp salt, 1 tb garlic powder, 1 tb dried rosemary. line them up in a single layer on a parchment lined baking sheet. bake for 20-22 minutes, flipping at the half way point. sprinkle with sea salt flakes!
-

Finally made it to Mayflower restaurant (Hong Kong flower lounge) for dim sum - it’s very close to SFO. The service is very friendly (honestly i don’t care if service is bad as long as the dim sum is good but this is a plus). Their zha liang (steamed rice rolls that are usually filled with Chinese donut/you tiao) is filled instead with deep fried bean curd skin wrapped shrimp. Quality is top notch but i personally prefer the original zha liang. Still, a very satisfying meal. We had Siu mai, shrimp dumplings, spareribs, chicken feet and this egg plant thing filled with shrimp paste. All were delicious.
.
. 📍: 51 Millbrae Ave, Millbrae, California .

caption_text:
Happy (toast) Tuesday! This toasted egg sandwich with smashed avocado is 100%! I mixed 1 hard boiled, pasture-raised egg with 1 tbsp avocado mayonnaise and 1 tsp dijon mustard, and spread it on top of some micro greens on 1 slice of toasted sprouted grain bread, then added some smashed avocado seasoned with salt, pepper and a squeeze of lemon, and finished with some sauteed organic spinach and the other piece of toasted bread. I usually use untoasted bread for my sandwiches but once in a while it's good to switch things up, and the toasting of the bread gives it additional texture. Speaking of texture, I paired this sandwich with a side of @fitjoy crunchy, addictive nacho cheese puffs - these are conveniently portioned, and contain 3-4 net carbs and 17-18G protein per bag, and are #grainless and #glutenfree. The nacho cheese flavor is very tasty and I love the crunchy texture! More dEATS and a discount code in my IG stories 🧀😋 #fitjoypartner

Homemade Taiwanese Beef Noodle Soup by my wife using @thewoksoflife recipe. 🐄🍜 It has been too hot the past few weeks to make ramen. So the day we made beef noodle soup, our place got up to 90 degrees inside so we finally budged and turned on the AC. Fall cannot come soon enough, but for now I will have to sweat it out while my broth turns my place into a sauna.
Of course I had to use ramen noodles in my bowl. The temomi noodles from @sunnoodles was pretty good, but the noodles for beef noodle soup needs to have a higher hydration for a chewier bite. We used udon for our second time which paired very well.

Mushroom Paitan Ramen from last week 🍜🍄. I used the Vegan Ramen recipe from my blog as a base and added a Ajitama because I could not resist. I would usually add a roasted vegetables to this dish, but these noodles booked end a yakitori night so I held back.

I am getting hungry just thinking about it.
[013] Tonkotsu Ramen 🍜🐷 - I hardly make Tonkotsu, but I have to admit this was really good. Added some gyofun which really completed the bowl. Time to turn this into tsukemen next.

My homemade ramen noodles after a week of resting. They have developed a slurpier and smoother texture.

Even though these noodles are at 36% hydration, they have a slight hard bite to them similar to hakata style noodles. It might be that whole wheat flour needs more water that just bread flour by itself.

I am ready to move on to my next batch so I can learn more. 👨🏻‍🔬 Definitely going to make less than 10 servings though. I don't eat as many noodles as I used to.

Shoyu Ramen testing 🍜🧪 I cracked open a few bottles of soy sauce that I had in my pantry for a while. The one that got my attention is a double brewed (saishikomi) soy sauce. This is where the produces uses already brewed soy sauce in the place of water and salt in the normal brewing process. It is not overly salty, but has an intense umami flavor that almost tasted fishy to me.

I am hoping to make a simple recipe that anyone can make at home. This recipe is so far so good! I want to tweak it a bit before posting. The made the bowl with some homemade noodles and I am pretty satisfied with how it turned out!

Who else likes shoyu ramen? I haven't really been a big fan, but I am getting more and more into it!

Thinking about the #noodles I had at @afuripdx. I learned that Afuri decided to have it's first US location in Portland because their soft and pure water similar to what is going in Japan. Perfect for making noodles. I still have a lot of things to learn about noodle making! 🍜 #liftingnoodles

This weekend was one of the rare times that I make ramen for my parents. I do see my parents once a week, but I have been very fortunate and spoiled to have a home cook meal prepared for me when I visit.

When I do cook for my parents, I want to make it special, yet simple and healthy. I started with a very simple chicken stock made from @maryschicken. The stock was so clean and refreshing it was worth spending a few extra bucks. The golden broth was combined with a Mushroom Shoyu Tare leftover from my last popup. I topped the bowl with some asparagus sauteed in garlic, some kurobuta tenderloin, and of course a marinade egg.

My parents are people of few words when it comes to describing tasty food, but will speak volumes when they eat something they don't like. I didn't hear any complaints and my mom saved her leftover broth for later, so I will take that as a win.

Cooking at my parents house always reminds me of the beginning of my ramen journey. It is always good to reflect on the past every once and a while and evaluate my progress before looking towards the future and seeing what is next.

I’ve been traveling for the last few weeks so bear with me and my non-NC posts but I can’t help but share! We all know that I’m a snob when it comes to boba and Raleigh doesn’t have a lot of good spots, so I’ve been making it a point to hit all of them in CA. I’ve been dying to get my hands on @tigersugar.usa but since they aren’t on the west coast yet, I heard @yifang.cal was a close second. There’s a trend happening right now where boba shops cook their boba in brown sugar and honestly, I don’t know if I can go back to regular boba now. It’s so high in demand and takes hours to cook so if you’re not there when they come out, you’re not getting your hands on it. It’s usually served with fresh milk but I got mine with black milk tea! Swipe for the most satisfying mix ever 🤤
I like that @tildenhotel guests have access to free coffee and water and a discount to all food and beverage orders. Jameel from the Tilden Cafe created the best hot mocha I have ever tasted! ❤️

One of my favorite food is Japanese food. Even before visiting Japan, I am always obsess about their culture rather it is anime, food, oisen, sake/whiskey, Nintendo, shrines etc. Among all the Japanese food, I tend to eat a lot of sushi and sashimi and I am a die hard fan of uni (sea urchin) and Toro (fatty tuna). Lucky for us, you can find Toro in a lot of places now such as @cornerbyspoonandfork and they are inexpensive. Once you try Toro, Otoro, or Chutoro, it's hard to go back to regular tuna. i made some PALEO TAHINI FOCACCIA with fresh herbs and sea salt using @simplemills artisan bread mix and i feel like a tahini ninja, what ever that is 🤷🏻‍♀️ anyway, greg is having a minor surgery today so i’ll be spending the rest of the day taking care of him, so i’m leaving you with these baddies and signing off—you can pick up the @simplemills bread mix over at @wholefoods (i found it in the baking aisle!). it’s so easy and you won’t believe how tasty!
.
one package @simplemills artisan bread mix
2 tb olive oil
3 tb tahini
1 tb water
2 tb apple cider vinegar
2 organic pasture raised eggs
toppings: chopped herbs of choice (i used chives and microgreens) and sea salt
.
in a medium bowl, whisk together the wet ingredients. slowly add the bread mix, and stir until combined. let sit for four minutes. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. form a ball with the dough. wet hands so dough doesn’t stick to your hands and place it on the parchment paper, and flatten evenly into a rectangle shape, about 1/2 inch thick. bake for 15 minutes. remove from oven and top with herbs and sea salt. boom there it is 💥 #kalejunkie #simplemillspartner

happy easter, friends!! 🐣🐰 there are so many new peeps around here (hi!! 👋🏼), i’ll do a proper intro soon so that i can get to know YOU guys too!! in the meantime, here’s my Faux Reese’s Peanut Butter Cup recipe, because there’s still time to make them and impress your friends and fam today! 😉

here’s what you need:
1 cup creamy peanut butter
2 tb coconut flour
3 tb maple syrup
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
1 tsp coconut oil
1/4 cup cacao nibs (optional, but adds crunch)

here’s how to make them:
line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a large bowl, whisk together peanut butter, coconut flour, and maple syrup. dough should be thick. form 12-14 balls and place them on the parchment paper. then form each one into an egg shape. place in freezer for 20 minutes. make then chocolate dipping sauce by melting the chocolate and coconut oil in a bowl in the microwave in 30 second increments, until smooth and liquidy. fold in cacao nibs. remove eggs from the freezer and dip each one in the chocolate and place back in the sheet. repeat until all are covered in chocolate. place into the fridge for 20-30 minutes to harden. #kalejunkie

oh hi friends 👋🏼 my girl @lizmoody inspired me to share a smoothie recipe, so today i’m sharing my usual “go to” — because when i’m not eating my own baked goods, there’s a pretty good chance i’m downing a smoothie or bone broth (if you know me, you know 😜) this recipe contains maca, which is probably my favorite superfood of all time, because i love the malty taste AND because it’s so great for hormone balancing. these days i’m also loving using collagen powder instead of traditional protein powders because it doesn’t have any funky taste. if you are vegan, replace with your favorite plant based protein powder! and...if i use this recipe post workout, i add BCAA + glutamine to reduce muscle soreness and omit the avocado🤷🏻‍♀️
✨
STRAWBERRY MACA SMOOTHIE
one cup spinach
1/2 frozen banana
3/4 cup frozen strawberries
1/2 avocado (them fats that make a smoothie so nice and creamy and thiqqqqq)
1 tb maca
1 tb hemp hearts
1 scoop collagen powder
1 1/2 cups non dairy milk
✨
toss everything in the blender (@vitamix is my fav) and blend until fully blended. you might have to take the top off a few times to scrape the sides, and adjust liquid as needed. enjoyyyyyyyy! 🥰 #kalejunkie

When @spicysound recommended this Spicy Pasta Orleans from Brenda's, I didn't expect it to be so addicting. The dish boasts four types of protein: sautéed shrimp, crawfish, mussels and andouille sausage. The fusilli pasta is the perfect shape to hold the thick red pepper garlic cream (droool) sauce. Even after finishing the food, my friends and I kept the empty plate of sauce to dip our beignets in!
.

You should’ve seen the look on my face when i took my first sip of the Black Sesame Latte.
i can’t even begin to describe how amazing this place was, so just fly to SF and see for yourself. ☕️ Black Sesame Latte ($6.75) was outrageously expensive but was out. of. this. world.
nutty, creamy, totally black sesame-y, and just the right bit of sweetness (i got my half sweet btw)
🍪 Matcha White Chocolate Cookie ($3) also hella pricey for a smol litto cookie that i could’ve easily finished in a bite but Stonemill knows how to make a good cookie - dense, moist, and soft 🍫 Black Sesame Chocolate Tart ($7) was crazy delicious. chocolate tart shell, matcha & black sesame layers under a rich ganache, topped with chocolate pearls and matcha sable
This place has stolen my heart and also the title for my favorite place in SF so far (sorry, Mr. Holmes) 🖤🍵💚

Come for the pizza.... stay for the buffalo chicken parm sandwich 🤤. And maybe the biggest curveball — this gem is at a pizza place!! 🤭🤭🤭

✨ One Night Special ✨
This Friday at Off the Grid: Fort Mason Center, we’re bringing you a rare opportunity to taste Southern California's famous Bred's Nashville Hot Chicken! //
The owners, Scott and Laura, had a dream of opening a chicken and waffle restaurant and began researching fried chicken recipes. During their research, they stumbled upon a new style of chicken which included two of their favorite ingredients, chicken (of course), and spice. After spending six months of testing and tasting chicken recipes, and another six months of tweaking their umami, they were finally ready to open their mobile food kitchen.
With an all-out, constantly moving mobile pop-up kitchen, they've learned to live by their slogan..."Chicken Ain't Easy"

friday, we made it, and i’m exhausted 🤣 living my best #grandmalife 🤷🏻‍♀️ starting the day with a boat load of my TWO-INGREDIENT CHERRY CHIA JAM 🍒 on top of gluten free sourdough and almond butter! once you make your own jam, you’ll never buy store bought again! it’s so easy and contains no added sugars or other weird preservatives! ✨✨✨✨✨
.
to make the cherry jam, you just need one cup of frozen cherries and 1/4 cup chia seeds (you can use fresh cherries, but you need to remove the pits). place the cherries and chia seeds in a small pot over low/medium heat, stirring constantly and mashing the cherries. after about 5-7 minutes, remove from heat and let sit for about 5 minutes, so that the chia gels and the jam thickens! store any extra in the fridge for up to one week✨ happy friday everyone!!! #kalejunkie

It has been two years since we've lost Gus and we still miss his presence greatly.
Despite that, we know that his vision and hands are on everything we do as a market. Gus had a heart for building long-term relationships with vendors, producers, and farmers throughout California, many of which we still do business with today. He loved San Francisco and always made sure to give back to local communities and causes that built up our neighborhoods. He put family first, including all employees, and always saw success as running a business that supports other families. Not a day goes by we don't run it like Gus is in it!
Thank you for everything--we love you, we love you! 💚

caption_text:
happy easter, friends!! 🐣🐰 there are so many new peeps around here (hi!! 👋🏼), i’ll do a proper intro soon so that i can get to know YOU guys too!! in the meantime, here’s my Faux Reese’s Peanut Butter Cup recipe, because there’s still time to make them and impress your friends and fam today! 😉

here’s what you need:
1 cup creamy peanut butter
2 tb coconut flour
3 tb maple syrup
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
1 tsp coconut oil
1/4 cup cacao nibs (optional, but adds crunch)

here’s how to make them:
line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a large bowl, whisk together peanut butter, coconut flour, and maple syrup. dough should be thick. form 12-14 balls and place them on the parchment paper. then form each one into an egg shape. place in freezer for 20 minutes. make then chocolate dipping sauce by melting the chocolate and coconut oil in a bowl in the microwave in 30 second increments, until smooth and liquidy. fold in cacao nibs. remove eggs from the freezer and dip each one in the chocolate and place back in the sheet. repeat until all are covered in chocolate. place into the fridge for 20-30 minutes to harden. #kalejunkie

Considering opening a hipster Japanese cafe in Brooklyn (or financial district in SF) and selling these caviar onigirazu (seaweed rice “sandwich” - like the sandwich cousin of onigiri). Would you buy it? How much would you pay for it? Just gauging the potential market before I quit my job and make this dream a reality 🎉 in all seriousness though, these taste amazing and much easier to make than I thought. I’ll record the step by step photos and share them with you soon - STAY TUNED! I used @petrossiannyc smoked salmon and daurenki caviar leftover from yesterday’s board. A fun way to switch it up from the usual sandwich for sure! Happy Friday! .

caption_text:
So glad I was able to get some delicious Russian food before I left the bay area‼️😍 It can be so difficult to find authentic Russian food that isn't crazy expensive. Have you guys ever tried it? Here are some of my favorite dishes 🔥
📸 Shchi: a Russian cabbage soup. It can be a bit on the salty side‼️🤤 (was too salty for @daofromsf hahaha)
📸 pelmeni: Russian dumplings filled with meat served in chicken broth 😍
📸 Blinchiki: Russian crepes filled with sweet cheese and served with jam. These were my absolute favorite- took me right back to my childhood ❤️ and of course, ALL Russian food is served with sour cream 😆 what would you go for first⁉️

here’s a little afternoon pick-me-up for ONE, because when it comes to desserts i really hate sharing. setting a great example for my boys, i know 😂🙅🏻‍♀️
.
STRAWBERRY CHOCOLATE CHIP MUG CAKE (mug cakes always inspired by my mama friend @sammyjaneeason)
.
4 strawberries, chopped into small pieces
1 egg
1 tb maple syrup
1/2 tsp baking powder
3 tb almond flour
1 tb coconut flour
2 tb dairy free chocolate chips
.
in a large mug, whisk together the egg and maple syrup. then add the rest of the ingredients and mix well, reserving a few strawberries and chocolate chips to sprinkle on top. microwave for 2-3 minutes. ENJOY!!!! #kalejunkie

Zha jiang mian - black bean sauce noodles. Step by step recipe is up on IG stories and in IG highlights! Many of you have asked if I have a blog. This is my blog, and I’ll continue to add step by step recipes to my highlights - feel free to browse up there and see what tickles your fancy. But as many of you already know and resonate, Asian cooking does not measure things down to the gram. I grew up watching my grandma and my mum throwing a spoonful of this, a splash of that, etc. as they go along, and that’s exactly what I do. Sometimes I offer rough measurements for those of you that want to see that, but I strongly encourage you to do the former (when you make Chinese food, not when you bake that angel food cake): taste as you go along. Certain things you can add more liberally (soy sauce, cooking wine) and others you start with little amounts (salt, sugar, sesame oil, fish sauce, vinegar... things that are stronger in taste) and adjust as you go along. Also a useful tip: if you feel that you’ve added too much salt, soy sauce, fish sauce or vinegar, one way to partially salvage a dish is to add more sugar. I use white or raw or brown sugar and it usually doesn’t matter which one I use in my recipes. But never artificial sweeteners. We eat a lot and we are fairly healthy and in shape. Everything in moderation and certainly no dieting over here 🙌🏻🙌🏻 .

In my happy place. It was such an overwhelming pleasure to be able to experience the early, mid and late summer menus at @singlethreadfarms this season and get to see the development of dishes as peak seasonality of products changed. Every meal I’ve had at ST has been flawless perfection, which can pose a problem for a restaurant in how do they top the last experience?when I decided to do this, I was nervous maybe there wouldn’t be enough variation in the menus month to month for me to keep the upward trajectory of smitten-ness going full steam but I needn’t have worried. Somehow I always leave even more blown away than my previous trip to ST which is so beautiful. The synchronicity between all the teams is unreal. Service is warm, welcoming and comfortable while being simultaneously the most polished of any restaurant I’ve ever dined in. I really love how the customized reserve pairings have evolved as Alex and Alex have gained more knowledge of my personal tastes (though it was always fucking mind blowing). @kyleconnaughton’s food is always B-A-N-A-N-A-S amazing, and there is enough turnover in the menu to support multiple trips in a single season. I’ll post up all the food pics in a few days time and sorry to be repetitive but as I rambled on about the last time, the food is emotional, both incredibly exciting and new while also concurrently deeply nostalgic and familiar for a northern CA kid who grew up eating so many of these same produce varietals @lumberjackieo grows at the farm from my grandparent’s ranch not 20 miles away and saw so many of the same flowers grown at my grandma’s Petaluma plant nursery. I’m very grateful that @light_thief’s birthday, my birthday and now our wedding anniversary all fall a month-ish apart each so I have the perfect excuse to do this shit every year now as long as I can continue to finance this addiction. Thank you to all y’all on the ST team who always make us feel like family when we are there and continue to make every meal newly the best of my life each time, over and over. Also, deeply, deeply appreciate you guys sharing some of that really special bottle with us. 🙏🏻
