We like it when you’re SAUCY! (especially our FRIED CHICKEN) 😏😜🍗🐔⁣
⁣
ARIA is this little gem 💎 of a restaurant located in San Francisco. 🌉 One of our favorite places to go to in the city. 🌃 The whole restaurant is covered with these really cool stickers and graffiti! 🌆 It has that modern street art pop style to it. It’s a small mom and pop take out restaurant with about 8 seats along a wall. Keep this in mind if you plan on dining in, otherwise take it to-go! We got a Combo C which serves 3-4 people. 👯‍♀️👯‍♂️Everything comes in these big ol’ trays so you know we had a ton of leftovers! 🥴😵 It comes with 10 boneless pieces of Korean Fried Chicken🍗, 10 pieces of Gangjung 🍗, Bulgogi Kimbap🍙, Spicy Pork Stir- Fry Ramen with an added Fried Egg 🌶🍜🐷🍳, Tteokbokki and Fries with White Sauce🍟. The crispy Korean fried chicken pieces are glazed in a sticky, sweet, and spicy sauce 🌶. The Tteokbokki and Spicy Pork Stir-Fry Ramen both have the perfect amount of spice! Nothing overbearing or less. The rice cakes are so soft and chewy. The Spicy Pork Stir-Fry Ramen is a bit on the spicier side. 🔥 They add a bunch of pieces of pork belly! Make sure to add a fried egg and cheese. The Bulgogi Kimbap is made with Rib-Eye beef 🥩 and comes with a lot of it! The Bulgogi is so tender. Love all the savory, sweet and pickled flavors. Also a great way to combat all the heaviness of all the other dishes. The White Sauce over the fries are so addicting! 🤤Everything made such a beautiful spread! 😍So aesthetic and colorful! Hope to be back soon for the AMAZING Korean Street Food! 🥰⁣
⁣
📍 ARIA Korean Street Food @ariakoreanstreetfood San Francisco, CA⁣
🍗🍜🍙🐷🐔🍟🍽 Korean Fried Chicken, Gangjung, Bulgogi Kimbap, Spicy Pork Stir- Fry Ramen with an added Fried Egg, Tteokbokki and Fries with White Sauce
[013] Tonkotsu Ramen 🍜🐷 - I hardly make Tonkotsu, but I have to admit this was really good. Added some gyofun which really completed the bowl. Time to turn this into tsukemen next.

Homemade Taiwanese Beef Noodle Soup by my wife using @thewoksoflife recipe. 🐄🍜 It has been too hot the past few weeks to make ramen. So the day we made beef noodle soup, our place got up to 90 degrees inside so we finally budged and turned on the AC. Fall cannot come soon enough, but for now I will have to sweat it out while my broth turns my place into a sauna.
Of course I had to use ramen noodles in my bowl. The temomi noodles from @sunnoodles was pretty good, but the noodles for beef noodle soup needs to have a higher hydration for a chewier bite. We used udon for our second time which paired very well.

I’ve been traveling for the last few weeks so bear with me and my non-NC posts but I can’t help but share! We all know that I’m a snob when it comes to boba and Raleigh doesn’t have a lot of good spots, so I’ve been making it a point to hit all of them in CA. I’ve been dying to get my hands on @tigersugar.usa but since they aren’t on the west coast yet, I heard @yifang.cal was a close second. There’s a trend happening right now where boba shops cook their boba in brown sugar and honestly, I don’t know if I can go back to regular boba now. It’s so high in demand and takes hours to cook so if you’re not there when they come out, you’re not getting your hands on it. It’s usually served with fresh milk but I got mine with black milk tea! Swipe for the most satisfying mix ever 🤤

here’s a little afternoon pick-me-up for ONE, because when it comes to desserts i really hate sharing. setting a great example for my boys, i know 😂🙅🏻‍♀️
.
STRAWBERRY CHOCOLATE CHIP MUG CAKE (mug cakes always inspired by my mama friend @sammyjaneeason)
.
4 strawberries, chopped into small pieces
1 egg
1 tb maple syrup
1/2 tsp baking powder
3 tb almond flour
1 tb coconut flour
2 tb dairy free chocolate chips
.
in a large mug, whisk together the egg and maple syrup. then add the rest of the ingredients and mix well, reserving a few strawberries and chocolate chips to sprinkle on top. microwave for 2-3 minutes. ENJOY!!!! #kalejunkie

welcome to muffin monday 🤷🏻‍♀️ or should i say CHOCOLATE CHUNK TAHINI MUFFINS and it’s probably a good idea that you call in sick from work today to stay home and make them, i’m just saying 😎 i’ve been getting a lot of requests for banana-free recipes, so here’s one for you guys. these muffs are also paleo friendly, dairy free, gluten free, grain free, and taste like they came straight from a bakery! the recipe makes 5 large muffins or 8 regular size muffins. here’s how to make them👇🏼
.
1/3 cup coconut flour
1/3 cup almond flour
1/4 cup coconut sugar
1/2 tsp baking soda
1/2 tsp baking powder
pinch sea salt
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1/4 cup @obourfoods tahini
2 eggs
1 tsp vanilla
3/4 cup @hukitchen chocolate gems
.
preheat oven to 375. line muffin tin with liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together all of the dry ingredients and set aside. in another bowl, whisk together the coconut oil, tahini, eggs, and vanilla. pour bowl with dry ingredients into the wet ingredients. fold in the chocolate pieces. use a spoon to fill the muffin cavities, making 5 large muffins or 8 regular size. bake for 20 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean. enjoy!!!!!!!!!! #kalejunkie

sunday calls for my PROCIUTTO, ARUGULA & LEMON PIZZA, made with a cauliflower pizza crust! it’s super easy to make, super flavorful, and yes—you can eat the lemon! if you want to try it in person, meet me tomorrow at the @specialtyfoodassociation’s winter fancy food show—i’ll be at the @caulipowered booth (#6719) from 11:30am-12pm, and they will be making them on-site. otherwise, go grab one of these pizza crusts and try the recipe!
.
1 @caulipowered plain crust pizza
1/2 cup pizza sauce
1/4 cup shredded sheep milk pecorino cheese
2 oz prosciutto
1 meyer lemon, thinly sliced
small handful arugula
everything but the bagel seasoning
.
preheat oven to 425 and place pizza crust on a baking sheet. spread a thin layer of pizza sauce evenly, followed by the cheese and the lemon slices. bake for 13 minutes. remove from oven, top with prosciutto, arugula and everything but the bagel seasoning. slice and enjoy! #caulipowered #ad

Okay fine, here’s a fall toast. Sourdough topped with labneh, apple cider jam and pumpkin butter from @traderjoes, honeycrisp apple slices, pepitas/pumpkin seeds, slivered almonds, and cinnamon. Obviously I got a little heavy-handed with the cinnamon but I convinced myself it looked reasonably like an intentional artsy plating concept.⁣
⁣⁣
You guys know I’m not crazy about sweets but I am a basic AF sucker for fall flavors. Plus, the savory tanginess from the labneh was definitely important on this toast. If you haven’t tried the pumpkin butter from @traderjoes I definitely recommend it. (Still not sponsored by Trader Joe’s.) It’s the most flavor-packed pumpkin spice product I’ve encountered. The apple cider jam is pretty good too—like something that falls somewhere between applesauce and apple pie filling.⁣
⁣
Btw, do you call it fall or autumn?⁣
⁣⁣

Happy hump day! Quick ramen bowl: seasoned them with some soy sauce, garlic, sesame oil, and sriracha 🔥🔥🔥 using instant ramen is so convenient when you’re short on time, and you can season it with your favorite sauces in the pantry 😋 added a @handsomebrookfarm fried egg for protein and some cucumber slices, avocado and @hamama_greens micro greens 👍🏻 my old face cleanser ran out so I just started using this @clarinsusa gentle foaming cleanser which has a lightweight, refreshing lather. I always need a cleanser that lathers! What about you? I chose the one for oily/combination skin (they have 3 varieties) and it has Tamarind Fruit Acid refines skin, helping unblock pores, and micro-pearls for exfoliating. At only $26 retail it will last me a good 3 months! Another beauty item targeting pores I’ve started using is @caudalie @mycaudalie vinopure natural salicylic acid pore minimizing serum. It is an ultra-light yet potent gel serum purifies pores, zaps blemishes, and purges excess oil, blackheads, and bacteria, the latter can result in pimples. My concerns are more about pore minimizing and it definitely makes the skin around my t zone more refined. I am looking forward to seeing the longer term results - it has 1000 reviews on Sephora with an average of 4.5 stars so it sounds promising 🎉 I’ve been paying more attention to skincare so I can minimize wearing foundation when I go out. Lately it’s been some @givenchybeauty prisme libre finishing powder + Healthy Glow Powder bronzer (pictured) and that’s it ☺️☺️🎉

Making Nalysnyky aka French crepes is the recipe that runs in our family through generations. The tradition started with my grandma and continues with me. Nalysnyky was the first dish I ever made for my friends when I moved to Kyiv and started my adult life. I still have the warmest feelings for these thin, buttery blini, which are mind-blowingly good when served hot straight from the frying pan. I always make them for my husband when he asks for something special for breakfast, and serve with homemade jam or quick fruit compote. If you're ready to master this dish, I have a perfect recipe for you: https://vivalafood.com/basic-crepes-recipe/
Happy cooking ❤️ #ukrainianfood #sovietishcooking

In my happy place. It was such an overwhelming pleasure to be able to experience the early, mid and late summer menus at @singlethreadfarms this season and get to see the development of dishes as peak seasonality of products changed. Every meal I’ve had at ST has been flawless perfection, which can pose a problem for a restaurant in how do they top the last experience?when I decided to do this, I was nervous maybe there wouldn’t be enough variation in the menus month to month for me to keep the upward trajectory of smitten-ness going full steam but I needn’t have worried. Somehow I always leave even more blown away than my previous trip to ST which is so beautiful. The synchronicity between all the teams is unreal. Service is warm, welcoming and comfortable while being simultaneously the most polished of any restaurant I’ve ever dined in. I really love how the customized reserve pairings have evolved as Alex and Alex have gained more knowledge of my personal tastes (though it was always fucking mind blowing). @kyleconnaughton’s food is always B-A-N-A-N-A-S amazing, and there is enough turnover in the menu to support multiple trips in a single season. I’ll post up all the food pics in a few days time and sorry to be repetitive but as I rambled on about the last time, the food is emotional, both incredibly exciting and new while also concurrently deeply nostalgic and familiar for a northern CA kid who grew up eating so many of these same produce varietals @lumberjackieo grows at the farm from my grandparent’s ranch not 20 miles away and saw so many of the same flowers grown at my grandma’s Petaluma plant nursery. I’m very grateful that @light_thief’s birthday, my birthday and now our wedding anniversary all fall a month-ish apart each so I have the perfect excuse to do this shit every year now as long as I can continue to finance this addiction. Thank you to all y’all on the ST team who always make us feel like family when we are there and continue to make every meal newly the best of my life each time, over and over. Also, deeply, deeply appreciate you guys sharing some of that really special bottle with us. 🙏🏻

[023] Karashibi Tori Paitan Ramen 🌶️🐔🍜 - I made a second iteration of my spice oil to mix with my thick and creamy chicken broth. *RAMEN FACT* In the word Karashibi, "Kara" is the typical burning heat from something like a dried red pepper or korean pepper flakes. "Shibi" is the numbing spice you get from a Szechuan peppercorn. So in Karashibi ramen, you the best of both worlds. A spice that affects both the taste and touch/feeling of your mouth.

The numbing spicd can mask the heat and flavor in a bowl or ramen, so it is good to bump of the flavors more than usual to make sure it doesn't taste "bland".
Ooey gooey deliciousness in the form of a grilled cheese. 🧀🧀🧀 perfect.

tested. retested. and tested again, here is the recipe for my new PALEO LEMON POPPYSEED MUFFINS 🍋 eeeeeeeeek they are so good, and i think some of my taste tester friends would agree (tell us, what did you think @biohackertodd? 😉) note, i haven’t tested all the substitutions, so if your diet allows, i’d suggest just making them as is! 🍋
-
here’s what you need for the muffins:
2 1/4 cups almond flour
1/2 cup arrowroot flour
3 eggs
1/2 cup lemon juice (this is 4-5 lemons)
zest of two lemons
1/2 cup maple syrup
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1 1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp baking soda
3 tb poppyseeds
1/4 tsp cinnamon
1/2 tsp salt
-
here’s how to make them:
preheat oven to 350. line a muffin tin with 12 liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together the eggs, lemon juice, lemon zest, maple syrup, coconut oil, and vanilla extract. you can also use a hand mixer to do this, but it’s not necessary. in another medium bowl, mix together the almond flour, arrowroot flour, baking soda, poppyseeds, cinnamon, and salt. pour dry batter into the wet, mixing together, but being careful not to overmix. use a spoon to fill each muffin tin cup almost to the top. bake for 17-18 minutes—the top will start to brown and a toothpick will come out clean.
-
for the drizzle, you’ve got options:
if you like your muffins a little sweeter, whisk together 1 cup of powdered sugar and 3 tb water, until desired consistency is reached, and drizzle over each muffin.
you could also whisk together 1/2 coconut butter with 1/4 cup maple syrup, thinning with a little water as needed.
-
ENJOYYYYYY!!!!! #kalejunkie

Extra-spiced pumpkin spice Mexican hot chocolate muffins with sea salt! Getting on a flight later and most plane food grosses me out, so I’m packing these homemade muffins to bring with me, along with this beautiful box of calavera burnt caramel truffles I received from @recchiuticonfections. What snacks do you like to bring with you on a long flight?⁣
⁣⁣
I have a trusted pumpkin spice muffin recipe I’ve been making for years but when I received these Día de Muertos themed truffles, they inspired me to take the “spice” in “pumpkin spice” to the next level. I incorporated shards of spicy chocolate, flavored with cayenne pepper and cinnamon like the delicious hot chocolate I had in Mexico. To make them, I melted 1 cup of bittersweet chocolate chips in a double boiler and combined with 1 tsp cayenne pepper powder and generous dashes of cinnamon. Then I spread the chocolate on a lined baking sheet and stuck it in the freezer until it fully set, and cut it up into irregular pieces.⁣
⁣
I dislike Halloween celebrations but love macabre things, so I prefer to participate with Día de Muertos. (And they are not the same thing.) Sugar skulls, or calaveras, are decorated and placed on ofrendas to honor dead loved ones but I also learned that the celebration includes gifting more palatable chocolate skulls as a reminder of our mortality, and to therefore savor the sweetness of life. These melt-in-your-mouth truffles from @recchiuticonfections with their beautiful calavera design are totally perfect for this purpose. #Recchuiti⁣
⁣
Be sure to look out for my stories to see what adventures I get up to after I arrive at my next destination!⁣
⁣⁣

I tried Kuro Obi the other week - a fast food concept by Ippudo at the San Mateo Hillsdale mall. I am skeptical of fast food/mall ramen, but I figured it can't be too bad if it's by Ippudo... but curiosity killed the cat. 😿

The concept is pretty solid, however the execution wasn't there. The first thing I noticed was the tare. The server just had to put one full ladle into eat bowl, but it was haphazardly thrown in and maybe. 1/4 of it was spilled in the side. Since the tare has all of the salt an seasoning, you have to make sure that all of it makes it into the bowl. Second the person manning the noodle station did not have a timer. Some ramen chefs have a good sense of when the noodles are done and other noodles have a large window for when they need to be taken out. I do not think that this was the case.

So how was it? Both bowls fell flat. It was under seasoned and the noodles we're a little undercooked (my biggest pet peeve). The person in charge likely makes a test bowl ahead of time, and if everything is measured out and timed properly, I am sure it tastes just right. The staff that is actually making the bowl might not know what they are doing wrong, which is a little unfortunate since these bowls can be greatly improved with a little more TLC.

happy easter, friends!! 🐣🐰 there are so many new peeps around here (hi!! 👋🏼), i’ll do a proper intro soon so that i can get to know YOU guys too!! in the meantime, here’s my Faux Reese’s Peanut Butter Cup recipe, because there’s still time to make them and impress your friends and fam today! 😉

here’s what you need:
1 cup creamy peanut butter
2 tb coconut flour
3 tb maple syrup
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
1 tsp coconut oil
1/4 cup cacao nibs (optional, but adds crunch)

here’s how to make them:
line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a large bowl, whisk together peanut butter, coconut flour, and maple syrup. dough should be thick. form 12-14 balls and place them on the parchment paper. then form each one into an egg shape. place in freezer for 20 minutes. make then chocolate dipping sauce by melting the chocolate and coconut oil in a bowl in the microwave in 30 second increments, until smooth and liquidy. fold in cacao nibs. remove eggs from the freezer and dip each one in the chocolate and place back in the sheet. repeat until all are covered in chocolate. place into the fridge for 20-30 minutes to harden. #kalejunkie

did you know you can also BAKE Trader Joe’s cauliflower gnocchi and make a quick, one pan meal? they will still turn out nice and crunchy, and you can have dinner on your table in minutes! this is an ITALIAN INSPIRED ONE PAN CAULIFLOWER GNOCCHI and i’m super excited to tell you how i made it because you’ll be surprised how flavorful this meal is and how tasty healthy can be! again, ignore the preparation instructions on the gnocchi package and follow mine below!):
-
here’s what you need:
one package @traderjoes cauliflower gnocchi, frozen!
1/2 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
1-2 sweet bell peppers, roughly chopped
1 small red onion, thinly sliced
pinch chopped basil
2 tb avocado oil (or oil of choice)
2 tb italian seasoning
pinch of salt / pepper
parmesan cheese to top (optional)
-
here’s how to make it:
preheat oven to 425 degrees. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. combine all ingredients in a medium bowl and use your hands to ensure everything is coated well with the oil (if you use too much oil, the gnocchi will not be crunchy). pour contents from the bowl onto the baking sheet. bake for 20 minutes. remove from oven and use tongs to toss everything. bake for another 10 minutes. remove from oven and top with the parmesan cheese if you’d like! enjoy 😉 #kalejunkie

Finally made it to Mayflower restaurant (Hong Kong flower lounge) for dim sum - it’s very close to SFO. The service is very friendly (honestly i don’t care if service is bad as long as the dim sum is good but this is a plus). Their zha liang (steamed rice rolls that are usually filled with Chinese donut/you tiao) is filled instead with deep fried bean curd skin wrapped shrimp. Quality is top notch but i personally prefer the original zha liang. Still, a very satisfying meal. We had Siu mai, shrimp dumplings, spareribs, chicken feet and this egg plant thing filled with shrimp paste. All were delicious.

Summer melon, a dish that we will be saying goodbye to very soon as melon season comes to an end. A refreshing combination of cantaloupe, honeydew, piel de sapo, geisha, and canary melons to end our current fruit sequence. These various fresh melons are compressed in a syrup made from aromatic herbs such as mint, parsley, oxalis, and citrus marigold. Next, we make a melon sorbet and add a dry sake to balance the sweetness of the melon. The dish is finished with a chamomile gelee and garnished with citrus marigold.

🚨BREAKING NEWS!🚨It's been an amazing journey since we opened our first food truck in 2010 and the last several years we have been working night and day to get our first brick and mortar location up and running. We took the challenge of evolving from 6 food trucks to adding a brick and mortar incredibly seriously and spent the time and attention to detail necessary to create a space that speaks to the brand and experience you have helped us build over the past 9 years. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
We are beyond excited to announce that our restaurant in San Francisco Mission District will be opening on November 7th at 990 Valencia!! Expect a large outdoor patio space, a colorful front parklet, new food specials, beer & wine, custom drinks, Filipino inspired soft serve flavors, and that same family street food vibe that we've been serving up since day one. It's taken us many months to get to this point and we sincerely thank all of you for making this dream a reality for us! Smash the link in the bio for the full @sfchronicle article. #senorsisig

We like it when you’re SAUCY! (especially our FRIED CHICKEN) 😏😜🍗🐔⁣
⁣
ARIA is this little gem 💎 of a restaurant located in San Francisco. 🌉 One of our favorite places to go to in the city. 🌃 The whole restaurant is covered with these really cool stickers and graffiti! 🌆 It has that modern street art pop style to it. It’s a small mom and pop take out restaurant with about 8 seats along a wall. Keep this in mind if you plan on dining in, otherwise take it to-go! We got a Combo C which serves 3-4 people. 👯‍♀️👯‍♂️Everything comes in these big ol’ trays so you know we had a ton of leftovers! 🥴😵 It comes with 10 boneless pieces of Korean Fried Chicken🍗, 10 pieces of Gangjung 🍗, Bulgogi Kimbap🍙, Spicy Pork Stir- Fry Ramen with an added Fried Egg 🌶🍜🐷🍳, Tteokbokki and Fries with White Sauce🍟. The crispy Korean fried chicken pieces are glazed in a sticky, sweet, and spicy sauce 🌶. The Tteokbokki and Spicy Pork Stir-Fry Ramen both have the perfect amount of spice! Nothing overbearing or less. The rice cakes are so soft and chewy. The Spicy Pork Stir-Fry Ramen is a bit on the spicier side. 🔥 They add a bunch of pieces of pork belly! Make sure to add a fried egg and cheese. The Bulgogi Kimbap is made with Rib-Eye beef 🥩 and comes with a lot of it! The Bulgogi is so tender. Love all the savory, sweet and pickled flavors. Also a great way to combat all the heaviness of all the other dishes. The White Sauce over the fries are so addicting! 🤤Everything made such a beautiful spread! 😍So aesthetic and colorful! Hope to be back soon for the AMAZING Korean Street Food! 🥰⁣
⁣
📍 ARIA Korean Street Food @ariakoreanstreetfood San Francisco, CA⁣
🍗🍜🍙🐷🐔🍟🍽 Korean Fried Chicken, Gangjung, Bulgogi Kimbap, Spicy Pork Stir- Fry Ramen with an added Fried Egg, Tteokbokki and Fries with White Sauce

tested. retested. and tested again, here is the recipe for my new PALEO LEMON POPPYSEED MUFFINS 🍋 eeeeeeeeek they are so good, and i think some of my taste tester friends would agree (tell us, what did you think @biohackertodd? 😉) note, i haven’t tested all the substitutions, so if your diet allows, i’d suggest just making them as is! 🍋
-
here’s what you need for the muffins:
2 1/4 cups almond flour
1/2 cup arrowroot flour
3 eggs
1/2 cup lemon juice (this is 4-5 lemons)
zest of two lemons
1/2 cup maple syrup
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1 1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp baking soda
3 tb poppyseeds
1/4 tsp cinnamon
1/2 tsp salt
-
here’s how to make them:
preheat oven to 350. line a muffin tin with 12 liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together the eggs, lemon juice, lemon zest, maple syrup, coconut oil, and vanilla extract. you can also use a hand mixer to do this, but it’s not necessary. in another medium bowl, mix together the almond flour, arrowroot flour, baking soda, poppyseeds, cinnamon, and salt. pour dry batter into the wet, mixing together, but being careful not to overmix. use a spoon to fill each muffin tin cup almost to the top. bake for 17-18 minutes—the top will start to brown and a toothpick will come out clean.
-
for the drizzle, you’ve got options:
if you like your muffins a little sweeter, whisk together 1 cup of powdered sugar and 3 tb water, until desired consistency is reached, and drizzle over each muffin.
you could also whisk together 1/2 coconut butter with 1/4 cup maple syrup, thinning with a little water as needed.
-
ENJOYYYYYY!!!!! #kalejunkie

welcome to muffin monday 🤷🏻‍♀️ or should i say CHOCOLATE CHUNK TAHINI MUFFINS and it’s probably a good idea that you call in sick from work today to stay home and make them, i’m just saying 😎 i’ve been getting a lot of requests for banana-free recipes, so here’s one for you guys. these muffs are also paleo friendly, dairy free, gluten free, grain free, and taste like they came straight from a bakery! the recipe makes 5 large muffins or 8 regular size muffins. here’s how to make them👇🏼
.
1/3 cup coconut flour
1/3 cup almond flour
1/4 cup coconut sugar
1/2 tsp baking soda
1/2 tsp baking powder
pinch sea salt
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1/4 cup @obourfoods tahini
2 eggs
1 tsp vanilla
3/4 cup @hukitchen chocolate gems
.
preheat oven to 375. line muffin tin with liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together all of the dry ingredients and set aside. in another bowl, whisk together the coconut oil, tahini, eggs, and vanilla. pour bowl with dry ingredients into the wet ingredients. fold in the chocolate pieces. use a spoon to fill the muffin cavities, making 5 large muffins or 8 regular size. bake for 20 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean. enjoy!!!!!!!!!! #kalejunkie

if you are in a dinner rut and need something easy (basically me all the time🙋🏻‍♀️🙋🏻‍♀️🙋🏻‍♀️) then my new TOMATO & SPINACH PASTA WITH PISTACHIO “PARMESAN” recipe is for you. it’s gluten free, dairy free, and vegan, and you can easily customize to make it your own. not vegan? add some chopped sausage and ahhh i bet that would be so good too 😋 i’m off to therapy and then home to test my cinnamon rolls recipe before sharing it this week (SO EXCITED!). anywhoooo, here’s what you need to make this dish:
.
for the pasta:
2 cups cherry tomatoes
1 cup diced onions
1 large shallot, chopped
4 cloves garlic, mashed
1/4 cup olive oil
1 handful spinach, chopped
1 tsp salt
2 tablespoons italian seasoning
1 tsp honey
1 package pasta of choice (i used gluten free fusilli)
.
for the pistachio parmesan:
1/2 cup pistachios (unsalted)
1 cup nutritional yeast
1/2 tsp sea salt
.
prepare pasta according to package instructions and set aside. in a medium pan, add the olive oil and turn on low/medium heat. add onions, garlic, and shallots. stir for about a few minutes, keeping an eye to make sure it doesn’t burn. while that’s cooking, place the tomatoes in a medium bowl. use your hands and crush the cherries (just squeeze them!). pour cherries into the sauce pan, along with chopped spinach, honey, italian seasoning, and salt. bring to a simmer and cover for 30 minutes. to make pistachio parmesan, add ingredients to a food processor and pulse till you reach desired consistency. toss pasta with sauce and top with pistachio parmesan. inspired by @adishonhealthy #kalejunkie

happy saturday everyone! i’m finally rolling out my PALEO COPYCAT SAMOA RECIPE in case you want to do something fun in the kitchen this weekend! i forgot i teased it here on my page a few weeks ago and then didn’t share the recipe—i feel like i’m in a thousand places lately and forgetting things 🙊🙈! note, you need cookie cutters :) if you make these, be sure to tag me so i can share 😉 off to spend the day with my boys!
.
for the cookie base:
3/4 cup coconut flour
3 tb arrowroot or tapioca flour
1 tsp vanilla
1/4 cup maple syrup
pinch salt
1/2 cup coconut oil, melted
.
for the cookie layer:
3/4 cup unsweetened shredded coconut + extra to sprinkle on top
1/2 cup coconut milk
3 tb honey
3 tb almond butter
*chocolate of choice to dip!
.
preheat oven to 325. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together the ingredients for the cookie base, forming a ball. slightly roll and flatten onto the parchment paper. you need a 3 inch and a 1 inch cookie cutter. form 8 cookies using the cookie cutters. line them up on the baking sheet. bake 10-11 minutes until the cookies are just set and remove from oven. next, make the cookie layer. in a food processor, add coconut, coconut milk, honey and almond butter. the dough should be super thick and sticky. assemble the cookies — add about 2 tb of the cookie mixture on top of each cookie (I found it easiest to roll dough into small worms 🐛 and press onto each cookie). melt chocolate in the microwave in 30 second increments. drizzle chocolate on top of each cookie. add more shredded coconut if you’d like. place in fridge for 1-2 hours until set! #kalejunkie

Zha jiang mian - black bean sauce noodles. Step by step recipe is up on IG stories and in IG highlights! Many of you have asked if I have a blog. This is my blog, and I’ll continue to add step by step recipes to my highlights - feel free to browse up there and see what tickles your fancy. But as many of you already know and resonate, Asian cooking does not measure things down to the gram. I grew up watching my grandma and my mum throwing a spoonful of this, a splash of that, etc. as they go along, and that’s exactly what I do. Sometimes I offer rough measurements for those of you that want to see that, but I strongly encourage you to do the former (when you make Chinese food, not when you bake that angel food cake): taste as you go along. Certain things you can add more liberally (soy sauce, cooking wine) and others you start with little amounts (salt, sugar, sesame oil, fish sauce, vinegar... things that are stronger in taste) and adjust as you go along. Also a useful tip: if you feel that you’ve added too much salt, soy sauce, fish sauce or vinegar, one way to partially salvage a dish is to add more sugar. I use white or raw or brown sugar and it usually doesn’t matter which one I use in my recipes. But never artificial sweeteners. We eat a lot and we are fairly healthy and in shape. Everything in moderation and certainly no dieting over here 🙌🏻🙌🏻 .

Ricotta Gnudi with sweet corn, Riverdog Farms sungold tomato & espelette. Gnudi are gnocchi-like dumplings, but made with ricotta instead of potato, which results in a lighter and 'pillowy' dish.

Thinking about the #noodles I had at @afuripdx. I learned that Afuri decided to have it's first US location in Portland because their soft and pure water similar to what is going in Japan. Perfect for making noodles. I still have a lot of things to learn about noodle making! 🍜 #liftingnoodles

[022] Yuzu Shio Ramen - I made my version of Afuri's famous Yuzu Shio Ramen. My shio ramen isn't quite as delicate but it packs a flavorful punch that competes with the yuzu flavor. I will have to balance the bowl better next time. Fine tuning the subtleties of ramen is what mastering ramen is all about.

I didn't have any thin noodles on had but I used up the remainder of my temomi noodles from @sunnoodles.

[023] Karashibi Tori Paitan Ramen 🌶️🐔🍜 - I made a second iteration of my spice oil to mix with my thick and creamy chicken broth. *RAMEN FACT* In the word Karashibi, "Kara" is the typical burning heat from something like a dried red pepper or korean pepper flakes. "Shibi" is the numbing spice you get from a Szechuan peppercorn. So in Karashibi ramen, you the best of both worlds. A spice that affects both the taste and touch/feeling of your mouth.

The numbing spicd can mask the heat and flavor in a bowl or ramen, so it is good to bump of the flavors more than usual to make sure it doesn't taste "bland".

Tantanmen testing for my next pop-up on May 11th 👨🏻‍🔬🌶️. Stay tuned for more details.

I started with the mushroom/cashew base that I used for my latest Vegan Ramen and amped it up with some sesame paste, peanut butter, garlic, and soy sauce. It is always amazing to see how a few ingredients can transform it into something completely different. It is topped with a little bit of szechuan peppercorns and ichimi to give it a little kick. My chili oil is a work in progress, but the habanero peppers I added pushed it in the right direction.

Because my dad is retired he goes fishing twice a day, everyday at the American River. He is a fishing machine often catching 5 to 10 fish a day 🎣. The fish that he catches right now are Shad, known as a fish that has a "thousand" bones. My mom painstakingly debones the fish and makes fish cakes out of them. What is great is that the fish cake has zero flour and is all meat unlike the stuff you find in restaurants or supermarkets. They are an awesome duo that makes sure my fridge or freezer is always stocked. Lucky me!

Fishcake goes well with any kind of noodle soup especially tonkotsu gyokai. The soup has the richness from the pork bones and a smokey fish flavor from the seafood components. A match made in heaven. 🐖🐟🍜

happy saturday everyone! i’m finally rolling out my PALEO COPYCAT SAMOA RECIPE in case you want to do something fun in the kitchen this weekend! i forgot i teased it here on my page a few weeks ago and then didn’t share the recipe—i feel like i’m in a thousand places lately and forgetting things 🙊🙈! note, you need cookie cutters :) if you make these, be sure to tag me so i can share 😉 off to spend the day with my boys!
.
for the cookie base:
3/4 cup coconut flour
3 tb arrowroot or tapioca flour
1 tsp vanilla
1/4 cup maple syrup
pinch salt
1/2 cup coconut oil, melted
.
for the cookie layer:
3/4 cup unsweetened shredded coconut + extra to sprinkle on top
1/2 cup coconut milk
3 tb honey
3 tb almond butter
*chocolate of choice to dip!
.
preheat oven to 325. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together the ingredients for the cookie base, forming a ball. slightly roll and flatten onto the parchment paper. you need a 3 inch and a 1 inch cookie cutter. form 8 cookies using the cookie cutters. line them up on the baking sheet. bake 10-11 minutes until the cookies are just set and remove from oven. next, make the cookie layer. in a food processor, add coconut, coconut milk, honey and almond butter. the dough should be super thick and sticky. assemble the cookies — add about 2 tb of the cookie mixture on top of each cookie (I found it easiest to roll dough into small worms 🐛 and press onto each cookie). melt chocolate in the microwave in 30 second increments. drizzle chocolate on top of each cookie. add more shredded coconut if you’d like. place in fridge for 1-2 hours until set! #kalejunkie

PALEO PUMPKIN ZUCCHINI BARS are what’s new today! ✨ when i was little my mom used to bake with zucchini and i was like WHY. DO. YOU. DO. THIS. TO. ME. i just didn’t get it. but now i do! adding zucchini to baked goods is not only a great way to use up extra veggies, it makes everything so MOIST without a ton of added oil! these bars are sweetened with just one banana and some @wedderspoonofficial manuka honey. and they aren’t too sweet, they are just the way i like them 😋 click the link in my bio for the recipe! happy thursday ❤️ #KALEJUNKIE

here’s a little afternoon pick-me-up for ONE, because when it comes to desserts i really hate sharing. setting a great example for my boys, i know 😂🙅🏻‍♀️
.
STRAWBERRY CHOCOLATE CHIP MUG CAKE (mug cakes always inspired by my mama friend @sammyjaneeason)
.
4 strawberries, chopped into small pieces
1 egg
1 tb maple syrup
1/2 tsp baking powder
3 tb almond flour
1 tb coconut flour
2 tb dairy free chocolate chips
.
in a large mug, whisk together the egg and maple syrup. then add the rest of the ingredients and mix well, reserving a few strawberries and chocolate chips to sprinkle on top. microwave for 2-3 minutes. ENJOY!!!! #kalejunkie

tested. retested. and tested again, here is the recipe for my new PALEO LEMON POPPYSEED MUFFINS 🍋 eeeeeeeeek they are so good, and i think some of my taste tester friends would agree (tell us, what did you think @biohackertodd? 😉) note, i haven’t tested all the substitutions, so if your diet allows, i’d suggest just making them as is! 🍋
-
here’s what you need for the muffins:
2 1/4 cups almond flour
1/2 cup arrowroot flour
3 eggs
1/2 cup lemon juice (this is 4-5 lemons)
zest of two lemons
1/2 cup maple syrup
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1 1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp baking soda
3 tb poppyseeds
1/4 tsp cinnamon
1/2 tsp salt
-
here’s how to make them:
preheat oven to 350. line a muffin tin with 12 liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together the eggs, lemon juice, lemon zest, maple syrup, coconut oil, and vanilla extract. you can also use a hand mixer to do this, but it’s not necessary. in another medium bowl, mix together the almond flour, arrowroot flour, baking soda, poppyseeds, cinnamon, and salt. pour dry batter into the wet, mixing together, but being careful not to overmix. use a spoon to fill each muffin tin cup almost to the top. bake for 17-18 minutes—the top will start to brown and a toothpick will come out clean.
-
for the drizzle, you’ve got options:
if you like your muffins a little sweeter, whisk together 1 cup of powdered sugar and 3 tb water, until desired consistency is reached, and drizzle over each muffin.
you could also whisk together 1/2 coconut butter with 1/4 cup maple syrup, thinning with a little water as needed.
-
ENJOYYYYYY!!!!! #kalejunkie

i never really considered myself a MORNING GLORY MUFFIN kind of gal, but wouldn’t you know, here i am 👵🏼 i made a version of my girl @lauraleabalanced’s jumbo morning glory muffins, and yeah...pretty convinced that you’re going to be obsessed too 💯 you can find the original (banana-less) recipe on laura’s blog, and my version is here for you below! you can see what they look like inside on my IG stories. -
ingredients:
1 cup rolled oats
1 cup gluten free flour (or whole wheat or spelt)
1 banana
2 eggs
2 tsp baking soda
1 apple (i like pink lady)
2 medium carrots
1/2 cup raisins
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 tsp nutmeg
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup coconut sugar
2 tsp vanilla extract
1/2 cup walnuts, chopped
pinch sea salt
-
instructions:
preheat oven to 350 and line a muffin tin with liners. in a medium bowl, mix together 1/2 cup of the oats, baking soda, flour, sea salt, coconut sugar, cinnamon, and nutmeg. set aside. in a food processor or blender, add remaining oats and pulse/blend until a flour consistency is formed, set aside. in another bowl, whisk together the eggs, vanilla, and coconut milk. next, core the apple, peel carrots, and add them to the blender, along with the banana. pulse/blend lightly until a crumble like consistency is formed. pour wet ingredients into dry, and fold in the raisins and walnuts, be sure not to overmix! spoon batter into each muffin cavity. i made regular size muffins and 28 min in the oven was perfect!
HAPPY SATURDAY! #kalejunkie

My homemade ramen noodles after a week of resting. They have developed a slurpier and smoother texture.

Even though these noodles are at 36% hydration, they have a slight hard bite to them similar to hakata style noodles. It might be that whole wheat flour needs more water that just bread flour by itself.

I am ready to move on to my next batch so I can learn more. 👨🏻‍🔬 Definitely going to make less than 10 servings though. I don't eat as many noodles as I used to.

Tantanmen testing for my next pop-up on May 11th 👨🏻‍🔬🌶️. Stay tuned for more details.

I started with the mushroom/cashew base that I used for my latest Vegan Ramen and amped it up with some sesame paste, peanut butter, garlic, and soy sauce. It is always amazing to see how a few ingredients can transform it into something completely different. It is topped with a little bit of szechuan peppercorns and ichimi to give it a little kick. My chili oil is a work in progress, but the habanero peppers I added pushed it in the right direction.

good morning! 👋🏼 the weekend wouldn’t be complete unless cookies were involved in my life somehow 🤷🏻‍♀️ i made my bestie @melissas_healthykitchen’s 5-ingredient CASHEW BUTTER DIPPED COOKIES and they are now a family fav!!!!! super easy to make and they are grain free and can be made vegan too! i’m sure you can substitute for another nut butter if cashew isn’t your thing!
.
1 cup cashew butter
1/2 cup coconut sugar
1 egg (or flax egg)
1/2 cup dairy free chocolate chips
1/4 cup chopped cashews
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix the cashew butter, coconut sugar, and egg. there should be no clumps. use a cookie scoop and form cookies, placing each on on the baking sheet. use a fork to flatten each cookie. bake 8-10 minutes. once cool, melt chocolate and gently dip each one in chocolate and sprinkle chopped cashews on top. that’s it!!!! #KALEJUNKIE
